<HEADLINE> Protected Bird Returned to Natural Habitat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhasa, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A Falco Cherrug, a rare bird
under national protection, was returned to the wild this morning
outside Lhasa, capital of southwest China's Tibetan Autonomous
Region.
</P>
<P>
Forestry and animal protection workers in Amdo County, Nagqu
Prefecture, seized the bird on August 28 from three Pakistani
poachers who had illegally captured the animal.
</P>
<P>
The bird was released today after two months of intensive care
rendered by animal protection personnel.
</P>
<P>
Experts estimate that the population of Falco Cherrug in Tibet,
which helps to control mice, at only several thousand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
