<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Urged to Improve Export Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's trade promotion body
Zimtrade said today the country's export and business environment
remained unattractive during the year ended June 30, 1997 due to
a lack of new export incentives to stimulate business activities.
</P>
<P>
''Zimtrade has made frequent recommendations on fiscal and
monetary policy issues which we felt are necessary if the country
is to restore macro-economic stability," Zimtrade's Chairman
Paddy Zhanda said in his report for the period.
</P>
<P>
He added, "Such suggestions, if accepted, would significantly
improve the trading and general business environment,''
</P>
<P>
The recommendations included calls to improve the
administration and efficiency in the tax system, to take trade
and other types of financing easily available and accessible at
reasonable cost and to redress the budget deficit and problems
related to it.
</P>
<P>
''To improve the trading environment and broaden the tax
base,'' Zhanda said, ''Zimtrade recommended that the value added
tax (vat) system be adopted to replace the existing sales tax
system.
</P>
<P>
''The government is, therefore, urged to involve the business
sector in the design of the vat system, followed by a thorough
educational campaign on all aspects of implementing the new
system,'' Zhanda said.
</P>
<P>
He said the trade promotion body had called for the
restructuring of the tariff regime, improvement of the existing
export incentives and the formulation of an industrial policy
founded on trade efficiency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
