<HEADLINE> UK Retail Sales Fall Sharply in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Retail sales in Britain recorded
its biggest one-month fall for six and a half years last month
after being hit by the death of Diana, Princess of Wales, and
unseasonably warm weather.
</P>
<P>
According to figures released by the Office for National
Statistics (ONS), retail volumes fell by 1.9 percent in September,
the biggest decline since April 1991 and much larger than what
economists had expected.
</P>
<P>
Last month's surprise fall slowed the annual growth rate from
August's 5.4 percent to 3.7 percent over the 12 months to
September.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said that sales volumes fell in all categories of
retailing during last month, but household goods stores suffered
the sharpest drop, with monthly sales volumes down 5.6 percent
compared with August.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, clothing and footwear also showed a sharp decline of
2.7 percent due to unusually warm weather.
</P>
<P>
The figures made many analysts predict that interest rates may
stay on hold next month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
