<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1630 GMT, October 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS -- South African President Nelson Mandela left Tripoli
today after a two-day visit to Libya, the Libyan official news
agency JANA reported.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference before his departure, Mandela declared
that he came to Libya to thank Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi and
the Libyan people for their support to South Africa and also to
extend help to the Libyans in regards to the U.N. sanctions on
Libya.
</P>
<P>
This was Mandela's first visit to Libya since he became
president of South Africa in 1994.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat left Gaza today for a Europe tour, which will take
him to France and Germany.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day visit, Arafat is scheduled to hold talks
with French and German leaders on issues concerning the Middle
East peace talks and ask them to render assistance in pushing the
peace process forward, according to the Jerusalem Media and
Communication Center.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian news service said Arafat will also visit the
Hague, where he will address a European Union conference on recent
developments of the Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The chief of staff of the Russian army today paid
his first visit to his country's Cold-War arch rival, the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
Colonel-General Anatoly Kvashnin, chief of the Russian
Federation Armed Forces General Staff, met Military Committee
Chairman General Klaus Naumann, NATO's highest military authority,
and NATO Secretary General Javier Solana.
</P>
<P>
Kvashnin was accompanied on his trip by the newly-appointed
Russia's military representative to NATO, General-Lieutenant
Viktor Mikhaylovich Zavarzin.
</P>
<P>
HONG KONG -- Hong Kong's stock market fell today for the fourth
day this week, dropping by 1,211.47 points to close at 10,426.30.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index, the key indicator of Hong Kong's blue
chips, broke through the 10,000-point level in morning trading to
9,998.07, down 1,639.7 points, before recovering a little in
afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
The morning plunge was the biggest drop in points in the
market's history and the largest percentage fall since October 26,
1987, when the market plummeted 1,120.7 points to close at
2,241.69, analysts here said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
