<HEADLINE> Alcohol: Culprit to S. African Traffic Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Alcohol has resulted in
4.8 to 16 percent of road deaths in South Africa, according to
the nation's Department of Transport.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the department's "Arrive Alive" campaign
warned motorists that they would be harshly dealt with if caught
driving while their blood alcohol level was above the legal
limit.
</P>
<P>
Motorists found guilty of drunken driving face fines of up to
120,000 Rand (25,500 U.S. Dollars) and, or six years'
imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for the first 21 days of October showed that
alcohol played a role in at least 11.8 percent of fatalities
involving pedestrians in the Western Cape Province.
</P>
<P>
The worst accident recorded during the Arrive Alive campaign,
which started on October 1, in which 11 people died and 20 were
injured, occurred on Monday on road in KwaZulu Natal Province.
</P>
</TEXT>
