<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Woman's Status to Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Sharif Hassan, the
assistant general counsel of the World Bank pointed out today
that the feminization of poverty is a consequence of women's
unequal access to economic opportunities.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that 1.3 billion people are living in poverty,
and more than 70 percent of them are female, said Hassan.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening session of the East African Conference
on gender and the law at the United Nations Conference Center
here, Hassan called on participants to respect and protect
women's right.
</P>
<P>
He said, at worldwide 77 million girls of primary school age
are not in school, compared with 52 million boys.
</P>
<P>
"Cultural factors, early marriage, pregnancy and household
responsibilities all affect girls' enrollment," he analyzed.
</P>
<P>
Among the world's 900 million illiterate people, women
outnumber men two to one, he said, adding that in many parts of
the developing world, women do not have legal control over the
land they farm, even in female-headed households.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kebede Taddesse, the Ethiopian minister in charge
of social and administrative sub-sectors in the prime minister's
office, also delivered a speech at the session.
</P>
<P>
He said, "it would be hard to imagine that a truly democratic
political set-up and a sustainable socio-economic system can be
established without the full participation of half the
population, i.e. participation of women.''
</P>
<P>
"Empowering women is thus not only a political agenda but also
an economic need," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
K.Y. Amoako, Executive Secretary of the United Nations
Economic Commission for Africa (ECA), told the session that
women's low status and the discrimination against them is not an
accident in most African countries.
</P>
<P>
"The causes of women's subordination and unequal gender
relations are deeply rooted in history, religion, culture, in
laws and legal systems, in political institutions and social
attitudes," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Amoako called on the meeting to contribute to a rich dialogue
and exchange of experiences, resulting in practical and
implementable options that will improve the lives of women and
men in East Africa, particularly poor women.
</P>
<P>
Anatole G. Tiendrebeogo, Assistant Secretary General of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU), called for improving African
women's status and taking a close look at the gender issue.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting which is organized jointly by the ECA and
the World Bank is attended by policy makers and gender experts
from East African countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
