<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 17:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Rejects Turkish Security Zone in N. Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today reaffirmed its full
keenness on the integrity of the territories of Iraq in the face
of designs to set up Turkish security zones on northern Iraqi
lands, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement was made by Foreign Minister Amr Moussa to
reporters here today in comment on the decision taken by Ankara to
slice off parts of Iraq's northern lands and name them Turkish
security zones.
</P>
<P>
"Anything that jeopardizes the safety of the territories of
Iraq is a matter that Egypt would not condone, sympathize with, or
agree upon," Moussa told the press.
</P>
<P>
He recalled that the security zones theory is one that leads to
clashes rather than prevents them. "I do not think this is
something positive," Moussa said.
</P>
<P>
But Moussa said Egypt has not yet made any contacts with the
Turkish side over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Turkey said Wednesday that its troops established a secure zone
in northern Iraq in a new bid to seal its borders from attacks by
Kurdish rebels.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad lost control of the northern Iraqi region after the
Gulf War in 1991. U.S.-led warplanes monitor a no-fly zone to keep
Iraqi troops away from the region, controlled by rival Kurdish
groups.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's Kurdish rebels fighting for autonomy in Turkey's
southeast have taken advantage of the power vacuum, setting up
bases in northern Iraq to launch cross-border attacks at Turkish
targets.
</P>
<P>
The buffer zone was apparently established following Turkey's
latest military operation in northern Iraq this month in a bid to
wipe out the rebel presence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
