<HEADLINE> ILO Forecasts Further Job Losses in World Steel Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The 7 million workforce of the
world's steel industry faces further shake-up due to technological
change, environmental pressures and withdrawal of state ownership,
the Fiready saw the biggest job losses
in its steel industry, with the total number of steel jobs
dropping by more than 65 percent in 1975-95 in the European Union
(EU).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in the US and Japan, steel employment fell by 51
percent dy been lost in the
past five years in Russia, it was only the start and some 310,000
jobs, which represent more than 40 percent of the country's steel
jobs existing last year, will still have to be cut over the next
five years to keep the country's steel competitive.
</P>
<P>
The report also forecast that steel consumption in
industrialized countries will remain static or decrease slightly
in the coming decade while consumption in Asia, notably China, and
Latin America was predicted to grow strongly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
