<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Sell 10 Million Government Shares </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwait Investment
Authority (KIA) announced today that it would sell in public
auction 10 million government shares in a domestic company
next month.
</P>
<P>
A KIA statement issued through Kuwait News Agency said that
the shares owned by the Kuwaiti government in the Contracting and
Marine Services Company would be sold through the Kuwait Stock
Exchange at the nominal price of 370 files (1.22 U.S. dollars) per
share.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the proposed auction is part of the
privatization program launched two years ago in the country.
So far the program has raised more than 2 billion U.S.
dollars through selling the government shares in various
companies to public subscription.
</P>
<P>
KIA, the state-owned agency overseeing the privatization
program, owns 37 million shares or 50 percent of the issued
shares of the company. The shares to be put on sale accounts for
27 percent of the shares it owns in the company.
</P>
<P>
The KIA also planned at a future date to put on sale 25
million more shares for public subscription at a suitable
price that will be fixed later, the statement said, adding
that priority would be given to small investors.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait's privatization program set out to sell state-owned
stakes in some 62 companies and is due to be completed in
1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
