<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Peasants Complains About low Vegetable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Red pepper growing
peasants of Meskan-Mareko district in central Ethiopia said
although they have a better red pepper harvest this year,
plummeting price has affected their living conditions.
</P>
<P>
A report from the Ethiopian News Agency today said, the
district produced 72,527 quintals of red pepper on over 6,240
hectares of land this year, compared with 43,680 quintals last
year.
</P>
<P>
Although the output has increased by two-thirds, the peasants
complained loudly about the decline of their price by about a
half.
</P>
<P>
The current price for one quintal of red pepper ranges between
95 and 100 Birr (6.8 Birr equal to one U.S. Dollar) while it used
to sell at 140 to 165 Birr, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The bumper red pepper harvest this year has been made because
more peasants were incorporated into the extension program apart
from the use of fertilizers and the favorable rainfall in,the
area.
</P>
<P>
However, the report said, the decrease of selling price of red
pepper will affect more than 97,000 peasants who grow the
vegetable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
