<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Hails Ross's Visit as Success </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 23 (Xinhua) -- In contrary to the
Palestinian assessment, Israel today hailed the visit by
U.S. peace envoy Dennis Ross as a success in fully breaking the
deadlock in the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The state-run Israel Radio quoted Israeli officials as
expressing satisfaction that Israeli-Palestinian peace talks had
been resumed on all levels thanks to the intensive mediation
launched by Ross, who concluded today his five-day shuttle
mission.
</P>
<P>
During his stay here, Ross held several rounds of talks with
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat in efforts to
bridge the differences between the sides over advancing the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Ross also hosted meetings between Israeli Foreign Minister
David Levy and PNA deputy head Mahmoud Abbas (Abu Mazen) and
between Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai and Arafat.
</P>
<P>
He also participated in negotiations held on the committee
level to solve disputes mainly over the opening of the Gaza
airport and seaport.
</P>
<P>
The officials also expressed anger over the remarks made by
PNA spokesman Nabil Abu Rudeinah and Information Minister Yasser
Abed Rabbo that there had been no progress in
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations brokered by Ross.
</P>
<P>
Rudeinah even described Ross' mediation as a failure, warning
that the region could erupt into confrontation if the situation
continues.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials were apparently unsatisfied with Ross'
failure to persuade Israel to nail down an agreement on Gaza
airport and seaport, and to stop settlement activities despite
Arafat's promise to resume full security cooperation with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The PNA Cabinet called Wednesday night on the United States to
prepare well for the Levy-Mazen meeting scheduled for next week
in Washington, otherwise the peace process could be severely
harmed.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. government shared Israel's view that the
peace progress is advancing and some important steps forward had
been made during Ross' visit.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin said Wednesday
that Ros had narrowed some gaps between the two sides during his
visit. Specifically, there had been progress in talks of the
interim committees on the airport and seaport, as well as the
safe passage between Gaza Strip and West Bank.
</P>
<P>
But he added that there were significant real differences
that remained to be overcome, referring to the disputes over the
security arrangements in the airport and seaport, and the
Israeli rejection to halt its settlement expansion.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the Levy-Mazen meeting, to be hosted by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, would examine ways of
moving forward to the final status talks, which will deal with
key issues such as final borders, status of Jerusalem and return
of Palestinian refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
