<HEADLINE> Tsohatzopoulos: Clash With Turkey in Aegean Possible </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said today that he could not rule out the
possibility of a "major incident" between Greece and Turkey in the
Aegean Sea.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that the United States was exerting pressure
on both Athens and Ankara in order to defuse the crisis between
the two neighbors and settle issues which cause tension, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a closed-doors meeting of the Greek Parliamentary
Committee for Defense and Foreign Affairs, Tsohatzopoulos
expressed concern over Turkey's "provocative stance" and the
continuous infringements of Greece's flight information region
(FIR) and airspace violations by Turkish warplanes.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last month, Greek government spokesman Dimitris
Reppas said that as long as the crisis remained in Greek-Turkish
relations, there was always a possibility of an "incident"
involving the two count collided in the Aegean Wednesday, but
causing no injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
