<HEADLINE> Cameroon's Biya Won in Presidential Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, Octobe 23 (Xinhua) -- Cameroon's incumbent President
Paul Biya won re-election today with 92.57 percent of the votes
cast on October 12, announced the Supreme Court acting as
Constitutional Council in the country.
</P>
<P>
Biya who won a seven-year term this time has six rivals, all
minor politicians. The three main opposition parties did not put
up any candidates because they decided to boycott the election.
</P>
<P>
The president's nearest rival was Henri Hogbe Nlend of the
Union of Cameroonian Peoples who scored a meager 2.5 percent of
votes cast. Samuel Eboua of the Movement for Democracy and
Progress won 2.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon's three main opposition parties which between them
won 56 percent of the vote in the 1992 presidential polls
boycotted the election mainly because of the lack of an
independent watchdog.
</P>
<P>
Although voters were called upon to stay away from the poll,
most of the registered voters honored their civic duties.
</P>
<P>
According to the Supreme Court, 81.35 percent of registered
voters -- 3.4 million out of a possible 4.2 million -- took part
in the poll.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition earlier denounced the poll as rigged and
dismissed similar figures given by officials of the Biya
administration.
</P>
<P>
Biya, 64, took over in 1982 from President Ahmadou Ahidjo and
won 1984 and 1988 elections as sole candidate and 1992
multi-party elections.
</P>
<P>
Cameroon embraced multi-party politics in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Front, the National Union for Democracy
and Progress and Cameroon Democratic Union all won seats in
Parliamentary election in May.
</P>
<P>
They urged their militants to stage peaceful protests to
coincide with proclamation of results to mark what they called "a
day of shame". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
