<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Commonwealth's Appointment of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides expressed welcome today to the appointment by the
Commonwealth of an envoy for Cyprus, Cypriot News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon arrival in Edinburgh, Britain for the
Commonwealth summit on Friday, Clerides described the appointment
as "a useful development," enabling the organization to closely
follow the situations in Cyprus, according to the agency.
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Secretary-General Emek Anyaoku announced today in
Edinburgh the appointment of former Indian foreign minister and
his deputy Kris Srinivasan as the envoy for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said that the Commonwealth would play an important
role in solving the Cyprus problem, adding that "our aim here is
to further promote our views regarding a Cyprus settlement."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the European Union, the United States and
Britain all have appointed special envoys for Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third of the island following an abortive coup
by Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish Republic
of Northern Cyprus" recognized only by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
