<HEADLINE> Zambia, Namibia Sign Road, Transport Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Namibia here today
signed two bilateral road and transport agreements to facilitate
trade and free movement of goods and people between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Dawson Lupunga, Zambian
minister of communications and transport, said the agreements
indicate the mutual desire of the two countries in enhancing
their socio-economic relationship.
</P>
<P>
"This occasion marks the forging of even stronger ties between
the peoples of Namibia and Zambia and their two economies," said
Lupunga.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the road transport agreement is in line with
the general spirit of regional integration of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC).
</P>
<P>
The SADC, which has 14 members including Zambia and Namibia,
aims to promote regional economic integration toward a fully
developed common market.
</P>
<P>
Lupunga added that ever since the demise of Zambia Airways in
1994 when the national airline reduced its regional routes and
entered liquidation the next year due to heavy financial losses,
newly-formed private airways in Zambia have been unable to
provide services to reciprocate the services provided by Air
Namibia.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that with signing of the agreement, a Zambian airline
and freight operators will take up the challenge to commerce
operations to Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Hampie Plickta, Namibian minister of works, transport and
communication, said on the occasion that the agreements can only
promote bilateral relations between the two neighbors who share a
common border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
