<HEADLINE> ECOWAS and Sierra Leone Junta Talks Greeted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, October 23 (Xinhua)-- Prolonged shootings from light
arms and an outburst of civilian demonstrations from various
parts of the capital Thursday evening greeted the outcome of the
the meeting between the ECOWAS committee of five and
representatives from the military junta in Sierra Leone which
ended in Conakry, Guinea today.
</P>
<P>
When the news reached the capital, crowds chanting the "war is
over, we now have peace" came from spontanous demonstrations with
people holding makeshift placards, some of which reads, " Sierra
Leone has been saved from doom," "no more Alfa jets" and " Kabbah
has made Sierra Leone peaceful again."
</P>
<P>
From state house, guards left their security posts and shook
hands with passers by and Revolutionary United Front (RUF)
combatants stopped their trucks to hug anyone in sight.
</P>
<P>
From the Wilberforce garrison, one of the main military bases
in the country, soldiers dropped their guns to hug and kiss their
collegaues.
</P>
<P>
One soldier said, "I am happy because I can now talk openly to
my collegaues in the Nigerian contigent at Jui. We are no longer
enemies."
</P>
<P>
Residents near Jui reported that many Nigerian soldiers left
their trenches to venture into the open to wave at Sierra Leone
soldiers perched in a hill top some half a mile away.
</P>
<P>
There was no immediate reaction from head of state, major
Johnny Paul Koroma to the developments in Guinea but observers
said the open jubilation over the outcome of the talks will
demonstrate to the junta leaders that all Sierra Leoneans were
yearning for peace and to resume normal life which was disrupted
since the May 25 coup. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
