<HEADLINE> Stocks Plunge Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Stocks plunged worldwide today
after a market panic in Hong Kong aggravated fears about
deteriorating business conditions in major Asian countries.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell nearly 177 points in the
first hour of trading, and was down about 207 points at its
lowest after 1:30 pm. It began to rise a bit afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also slid more than 2 percent initially,
and declining issues outnumbered advancers by more than a 5-to-1
margin in midday trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
The damage was heavier on overseas markets. Tokyo's Nikkei
stock average fell 3 percent, Frankfurt's DAX index fell 4.7
percent and London's FT-SE 100 fell 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. Treasury bonds shot higher, helping cushion the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
The worldwide downturn was triggered by a shocking 10.41
percent tumble by the Hang Seng index of Hong Kong today that
deepened fears about the profits of American companies whose
business is closely linked in the Asian market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
