<HEADLINE> Clintons Host Child Care Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
opened a day-long conference on child care today, saying he hoped
it would "spur us on to find ways to help parents -- all parents
-- afford safe, affordable, high quality child care."
</P>
<P>
Clinton joined first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton today in
hosting the first-ever White House Conference on Child Care.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said, "Too often child care is unaffordable,
inaccessible, and sometimes even unsafe.... And government
assistance meets just about a quarter of the need."
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said, "Child care is
exceedingly important with respect to the health of our economy."
</P>
<P>
He urged more public-private partnerships to provide better
care, claiming it will increase worker productivity of an
estimated 20 million U.S. families with working parents, 8 million
with kids under the age of five.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called the issue "America's next great frontier" and
said that while federal assistance has increased by 70 percent
since 1993, more should be done.
</P>
<P>
Officials acknowledged additional strain is being caused by
last year's welfare reform law, which included only 4 billion
dollars over the next six years for states to help parents forced
into the workplace.
</P>
<P>
Clinton promised to develop a plan by his next State of the
Union speech. 
</P>
</TEXT>
