<HEADLINE> Turkey Protests Greek Harassment of Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry today
lodged a protest against the alleged harassment of a Turkish
submarine by a Greek minesweeper in the Aegean.
</P>
<P>
Counselor of the Greek Embassy in Ankara Alexander Couyou was
summoned to the ministry to hear the protest, the Anatolia News
Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minesweeper Monday tried to sail over a Turkish
submarine in the international waters of the Aegean and then
collided with a Turkish patrol boat nearby, causing light damage
to both vessels.
</P>
<P>
The two Turkish warships were conducting routine exercises in
the high seas, the foreign ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi also
criticized the provocative action by the Greek minesweeper,
describing it as "a very serious one."
</P>
<P>
"We are trying to refrain from provocations and to transform
the Aegean peaceful waters, but sometimes such incidents take
place," Karadayi said.
</P>
<P>
However, the Greek Defense Ministry has reportedly denied the
harassment charges, saying the collision was caused due to
Turkish warships' "dangerous actions."
</P>
<P>
The Greek and Turkish relations have been worsening since the
Cypriot government announced that it would not give up the
controversial plan to buy S-300 missiles from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Greece is an ally of the Greek Cypriots and Turkey one of the
Turkish Cypriots in Cyprus. Cyprus has remained divided into the
Greeck Cypriot-ruled south and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled
north since 1974 when Turkey landed troops and took the northern
third of the island following a coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
Greek and Greek Cypriot troops held joint exercises,
code-named "Victory '97", from October 10 to 14 in the Greek
Cypriot-controlled area, while Turkish forces and Turkish Cypriot
national guards responded with planned joint military drills for
early next month.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds over a number of issues,
including the mineral resources under the Aegean, airspace
division as well as the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
The two countries came to the brink of war early last
year over an uninhabited islet in the Aegean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
