<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta to Hand Over Next April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The military junta in Sierra
Leone that overthrew the legitimate government in the May 25 coup
today agreed to hand over power to the ousted president Ahmed
Tejan Kabbah on April 22 next year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, all the people, including the junta leader major
Johnny Paul Koroma, who are involved in the coup will be granted
amnesty at the end of the six-month transition period.
</P>
<P>
These are the highlights of a communique issued at end of the
talks between the junta's delegation and a sub-regional committee
of five foreign ministers in Conakry, capital of Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The communique also demanded that Kabbah government, when
restored, shall be all embracing, implying that all parties
concerned in the political crisis may have a place in the
government.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, from Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea, Cote d'ivoire and
Liberia, are mandated by the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) to handle the crisis in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Both ECOWAS and the United Nations are imposing sanctions
against the junta.
</P>
<P>
Since initial dialogue broke down last July when the junta
said it would stay in power until 2001, there has been a state of
virtual war between ECOWAS peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG and
the junta forces.
</P>
<P>
According to a document of the meeting, which started last
night, there should be a cessation of hostilities throughout
Sierra Leone with immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
ECOMOG force commander major-general Victor Malu, who is in
Conakry attending the talks, has declared immediate ceasefire
starting from the time the communique was issued this afternoon,
the British Broadcasting Corporation reported.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigerian foreign minister Tom Ikimi, who is the
Chairman of the ECOWAS committee of five, has agreed that rebel
leader Foday Sankoh "is a vital part of the peace process" in
Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Sankoh who has been in detention in Nigeria since March this
year is expected to be back in Sierra Leone to help promote the
peace process and stability of the country.
</P>
<P>
In Freetown, capital of Sierra Leone, jubilant people are out
to the streets, singing and dancing for there will be no military
intervention in the country.
</P>
<P>
But ousted president Kabbah, who is in Edinburgh, Scotland to
participate in the Commonwealth Summit scheduled to open
tomorrow, refused to make comment on the communique.
</P>
<P>
He said he had nothing to say until he was briefed of the
meeting in Conakry.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi was confident that the agreement will hold.
</P>
<P>
"I think we have the ability to manage it," he said, quoted by
the BBC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
