<HEADLINE> Trading Standard on UK Used Car Market Appalling: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The trading standard on
Britain's used car market is nothing less than "appalling" as tens
of thousands of consumers are cheated each year, according to a
report on the trade by the Office of Fair Trading (OFT).
</P>
<P>
The report said that each year some 8.2 million used cars are
bought and last year these purchases led to 84,479 complaints to
trading standards offices, more than for any other consumer goods.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that one in six buyers encounters a problem
within six months. Some 28,000 cars written off by insurers are
repaired by unscrupulous traders and put back on sale, and many of
the 500,000 cars stolen each year are resold to unsuspecting
drivers.
</P>
<P>
The report added that one in seven cars sold was also found to
have outstanding hire purchase or other debt attached to them and
some cars were in such bad condition that lives were put at risk.
</P>
<P>
The OFT called for new legislation aimed at eliminating some of
the worst abuses of the used car trade to be enacted which will
give trading standards officers powers to make on-the-spot
investigations of cars for sale and to detailed vehicle
decumentation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
