<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Won't Expel Nigeria: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Commonwealth of nations will
not expel Nigeria but may impose new sanctions on it, the
organization's secretary-general, Chief Emeka Anyaoku said in
London today.
</P>
<P>
"The exclusion of Nigeria is not on the table. It is not one
of the recommendations of the Commonwealth Ministerial Action
Groups (CMAG)," he was quoted by the News Agency of Nigeria as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku's comment came on the eve of the Commonwealth summit
of heads of state in Edinburgh, Scotland, on Friday, which is to
decide on Nigeria's membership of the 54-nation body.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth suspended Nigeria's membership in November
1995 after its government executed author Ken Saro-Wiwa and eight
other minority activists on charges of murder.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth then directed the CMAG to investigate and
monitor Nigeria's human rights record so that it can decide at
its next summit two years later whether Nigeria should be
expelled for good.
</P>
<P>
As the deadline draws near and consultations between CMAG and
Nigeria seem to have yielded no positive results, there is a fear
among some Nigerians that their country might be expelled after
all.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku explained that the decision not to expel Nigeria was
taken in the light of the local government elections on
multi-party basis last March, which has been generally regarded
as free and fair.
</P>
<P>
He, however, said the Edinburgh summit may impose new
sanctions on Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
It is understood that both Britain and Canada have been
pressing for further sanctions on Nigeria, insisting that the
country is not doing enough to improve its human rights record
and that its military government is not sticking to its
transition to civil rule program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
