<HEADLINE> S. Africa Builds More Clinics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A total of 164 new
clinics had been built in the first nine months of the year,
compared with 44 in the same period last year, the South African
Press Association quoted a Health Department official as saying
today.
</P>
<P>
Other 39 clinics were upgraded, Director Yogan Pillay told a
national health consultative forum in Pretoria. In addition, he
said, 51 mobile clinics had been delivered.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives realized by the department in the social
sector included abortion services in all provinces, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months since South Africa adopted abortion
law in February, nearly 13,000 legal abortions were performed,
according to a survey by the Reproductive Rights Alliance.
</P>
<P>
The new legislation allows state-funded pregnancy termination
in demand for all women over the age of 16 in the first 12 weeks
of pregnancy. Abortions for further eight weeks were subjected to
certain conditions.
</P>
<P>
On birth control, Pillay said the department was trying to
promote the use of condoms in high schools to reduce an 8 percent
birth rate among teenagers below the age of 16.
</P>
<P>
Other achievements include the distribution of more
wheelchairs and hearing aids and more surgery to remove eye
cataracts, the department said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
