<HEADLINE> US Senate Approves Temporary Spending Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhding
bill of current fiscal year expires today.
</P>
<P>
By a vote of 100-0, the U.S. Senate approved a stop-gap funding
measure that temporarily takes the place of a completed federal
budget.
</P>
<P>
The measure, which was approved by the U.S. House of
Representatives Wednesday, now goes to the White House for
signature. President Clinton has to sign it before midnight to
prevent many federal departments and agencies from losing their
spending authority and possibly shutting down.
</P>
<P>
The proposal keeps the government operating at current funding
levels unless U.S. Congress and President Clinton have agreed on a
lower amount.
</P>
<P>
Since fiscal 1998 began on October 1, the U.S. Congress has
finished work on seven of 13 spending bills. President Clinton has
signed five to cover the Pentagon and a myriad of military
construction projects, the Energy and Treasury departments, the
U.S. Postal Service and Congress's operations. 
