<HEADLINE> Israel Blasts Hamas Leaders for Inciting More </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Israel today strongly
accused Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed Yassin of inciting
more violence and attacks against Israel, while stressing that
Israel will continue its determined war against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Ministry made the accusation in a statement
issued here in its strong reaction to the tough speeches made by
Yassin and Hamas (Islamic Resistance Movement) political leader
Abdul Aziz Rantisi at a rally in Gaza Wednesday, in which they
called on Palestinian students to be ready to die for the fight
against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The statement expressed "shock and revulsion" over the Hamas
leaders' remarks, saying their action made it clear that Hamas
does not want peace and coexistence with Israel. It said that
inciters of terror and violence against Israel do not have right
to take part in the peace process, they will harm Palestinian
people too.
</P>
<P>
The statement stressed that Israel will continue fighting
against terrorism, and will call on international community to
denounce theses anti-peace actions.
</P>
<P>
It also demanded Palestinian National Authority (PNA) to "take
determined and consistent action against terrorists and their
infrastructure in the self-rule areas in order that the
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks will continue in the positive
direction."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to 5,000 students in the Islamic University Wednesday
night, Yassin said the world only understands the language of
force and the Palestinians must fight to resist Israel until they
have their rights.
</P>
<P>
Noting that "a nation without a holy war is a nation without
purpose," Yassin declared that "we'll continue our holy war
against our enemy (Israel)."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the same rally, Rantisi called on Palestinian
students to follow Yassin's footsteps and be prepared to die for
the cause. He said he wants to tell the U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, who labeled Hamas as enemy of the U.S., that
Hamas has a commitment to God to follow up on the holy war against
"Zionist terrorism."
</P>
<P>
This is the toughest speech that Yassin has ever made since he
was released from Israeli jail and returned to his home in Gaza
early this month.
</P>
<P>
In past speeches, the 61-year-old, wheel chair-bound and
charismatic Hamas leader softened his tone, leading to speculation
that he might consider having a cease-fire with Israel and joining
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has been standing firm against making peace with
Israel. The militant group has gained fame through launching a
relentless violent campaign against Israel by repeatedly sending
suicide bombers to blow up Israeli buses and markets.
</P>
<P>
In the latest two operations, five Hamas suicide bombers blew
up themselves in Jerusalem's two central markets, killing 20
Israelis and wounded more than 300 others, rendering heavy blows
to the Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israel is demanding the PNA to launch an all-out war against
Hamas and other militant groups so to advance the peace process.
</P>
</TEXT>
