<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-23 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Decision on MENA Conference to Be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's final say on whether it
will attend Middle East and North Africa Economic Conference
(MENA) will be announced within a few days, presidential political
adviser Osama el-Baz said today.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters here, Baz explained that Egypt's stance on
the conference stemmed from whether it would serve peace,
stability and regional cooperation in the Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
Baz's remarks appeared a bit confused with those by Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak who told the London-based Arabic daily
Al-Hayat that Egypt will only announce its decision on the Doha
conference just three to four days before its opening.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, it risks being accused of making decision hastily
and prodding others not to attend, Wednesday's Al-Hayat quoted
Mubarak as saying.
</P>
<P>
Qatar has invited 92 countries and organizations and expects
some 2,500 foreign participants to the annual gathering, which is
to be held on November 16-18.
</P>
<P>
"If no progress was made in the peace process, it would be
difficult to envisage how the Doha (Qatar) conference could be of
any use," Baz said and speculated an ensuing slim representation
at the conference.
</P>
<P>
In this case, it would fall short of realizing its original
target of buttressing regional cooperation, he added.
</P>
<P>
A number of Arab countries like Syria, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia
and the United Arab Emirates as well as the Palestinian National
Authority have threatened to boycott the Israeli-attending
conference in protest against Israel's hardline policy towards the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
More other Arab countries hesitate in announcing their
intentions, demanding a softened Israeli stance towards peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
