<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Cooperation in Petrochemicals Has Wide Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The China Petrochemical
Corporation hopes to expand cooperation with US partners in the
trade, science, technology and investment areas.
</P>
<P>
Sheng Huaren, general manager of the corporation, said his
company sincerly hopes that the government of the United States
will support and encourage US companies to export more new
high-tech technology and increase investments in China. He also
urged the US government to grant preferential loans to enterprises
engaged in cooperation, and make grant permanency to China's Most
Favored Nation (MFN) trading status in order to deepen bilateral
cooperation in the petrochemical sector.
</P>
<P>
The petrochemical sector is regarded as a pillar in China's
rapid and sustained economic growth, said Sheng, adding that
related bilateral cooperation should help to improve and develop
relations between the two countries, "China and the United States
should look at President Jiang Zemin's upcoming state visit to the
US as an opportunity to raise bilateral cooperation in the
petrochemical sector to a new level."
</P>
<P>
Sheng noted the remarkable progress in bilateral cooperation in
the petrochemical sector, and said that China introduced some 600
types of technology from abroad between 1973-1997. He said that at
least half of the imported technology came from the United States,
and noted that China will continue to introduce technology and
equipment from the US. Sheng noted that China will import some one
million tons of crude oil from Alaska.
</P>
<P>
Sheng pointed to China's vast potential market, and said the
petrochemical sector has a solid foundation and technology and is
staffed by well-trained technicians and management personnel. He
also noted that US companies offer advanced technologies, and
high-level international management and marketing experience.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation between the China Petrochemical Corporation and its
US counterparts is based on equality, mutual benefit,
complementary advantages, long-term collaboration and common
development, said Sheng. "The prospects for cooperation are very
broad."
</P>
<P>
Sheng also underlined that US-based Arco and Phillips companies
held their boards of directors meetings in China in 1996 and 1997
respectively, thereby indicating keen interest and confidence in
expanding their businesses in China.
</P>
<P>
The China Petrochemical Corporation, established in 1983, has
founded 10-odd joint ventures with US companies over the past few
years. The company currently refines 80 percent of oil, and
produces 75 percent of the nation's ethylene.
</P>
<P>
Sheng said that his company and US-based Exxon are currently
discussing plans invest three billion US dollars to set up a
refinery in east China's Fujian province, and is also conducting
feasibility studies with Dow Chemicals for a large ethylene
project in Tianjin valued at 2.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The China Petrochemical Corp. and Phillips are negotiating two
petrochemical projects in Shanghai and Lanzhou, with related
investments expected to exceed two billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, China Petrochemical has also cooperated with other US
companies, including Du Pont, Lubrizol, Hercules and Englhard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
