<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Premier Declares Close of National Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
declared on Friday the close of the 13-day Eighth Chinese National
Games.
</P>
<P>
Present at the closing ceremony in the Shanghai indoor-stadium
were Li Tieying, member of the Political Bureau of the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee and state councilor, Huang
Ju, member of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the ceremony were other leaders including Chi
Haotian, Luo Gan, Chen Muhua, Wang Guangying, Qian Weichang, Henry
Ying Tung Fok and Chinese sports officials.
</P>
<P>
A number of noted athletes who made great contributions for the
sports development in the country in the past four decades were
also honored by the Chinese officials during the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Some 7,600 athletes from 46 delegations participated in the
quadrennial sports festival which featured 28 sports with the
Chinese martial arts being the only non-Olympic discipline.
</P>
<P>
Remarkable progress had been made in the 11-day competition as
quite a few world and Asian records were broken.
</P>
<P>
In the swimming pool, the 16-year-old Chen Yan broke the
15-year-old world record in the women's 400-meter individual
medley by clocking four minutes and 34.79 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yanyan, 19, followed suit to better the world record in the
women's 200m individual medley in 2:09.72.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese swimmers also surpassed nine Asian records, and 10
gold medalists clocked the year-best times in the women's events.
The male swimmers also made striking progress by entering the
world top ten in five events.
</P>
<P>
In the track and field competitions, Jiang Bo clocked 14:28.09
and her teammate Dong Yongmei timed 14:29.82, both shattering the
newly-established record of 14:31.27 set by Dong in the heats.
</P>
<P>
The original world mark of 14:36.45 was set by Fernanda Ribeiro
of Portugal in Hechtel, Belgium on July 22, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Li Xuemei, 20, became the first Asian to break the 11-second
barrier in the women's 100 meters with the year's second best time
of 10.79 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Chinese strongwomen displayed their dominance by breaking all
the world records in the nine categories while their man
counterparts also surpassed six world marks in their 10-class
competitions.
</P>
<P>
When the Games concluded here in success, the Chinese athletes
were encouraged by the sports officials to keep training hard for
the coming world sports events, as the competitive atmosphere
abroad will be more tough.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth Chinese National Games will be held in 2001 in
Guangzhou, Guangdong Province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
