<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visiting Chinese Vice-Premier Meets Vietnamese Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo
met here today with Vietnamese Communist Party and state leaders
to discuss ways to further promote relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
On the second day of his three-day stay here, Wu talked with
Vietnamese Communist Party leader Do Muoi and the country's
newly-elected President Tram Duc Luong.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi told Wu that many existing conditions in Vietnam and
China are favorable for cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi expressed his belief that the two countries will score
new achievements as they work together in politics, economy,
trade, science and technology.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Wu said the Chinese government attaches great
importance to its relations with Vietnam and wishes to further
develop the friendly relations into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
While meeting Tram Duc Luong, Wu said China and Vietnam,
economically complementary, could bring their economic and trade
cooperation to a higher level through joint efforts.
</P>
<P>
Tram Duc Luong said the meeting of Chinese and Vietnamese
leaders on an annual basis serves as a guidance for the smooth
development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Wu has also met with Vietnam's Permanent Deputy Prime Minister
Nguyen Tan Dung.
</P>
<P>
He told Nguyen Tan Dung that good neighborly, mutually
beneficial and cooperative Sino-Vietnamese relations are in the
fundamental interest of both countries, and are conducive to
regional as well as world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
In general, the Chinese vice-premier noted, economic
cooperation and trade between the two countries are still at a low
level, and that there exists vast potential for their further
development.
</P>
<P>
China hopes to further bring forward its economic cooperation
and trade with Vietnam by diversifying the forms of cooperation on
the basis of equality and mutual benefit, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nguyen Tan Dung agreed with Wu and said the two sides will
discuss and turn the consensus reached earlier by senior leaders
of the two countries into practical cooperation programs.
</P>
<P>
He wished Wu's visit, the first by a Chinese vice-premier in
charge of economic affairs since the two neighboring countries
fully normalized relations in 1991, will be successful.
</P>
<P>
Also today, with Wu and Nguyen Tan Dung's presence, Chinese and
Vietnamese officials signed two documents on China's provision of
loans and aid to Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is the second leg of Wu's tour across Asia, which has
already brought him to Bangladesh and will further bring him to
Laos, Myanmar and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
