<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Day Marked In Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Vice-Foreign Minister
Li Zhaoxing said today at a reception for UN Day 1997 that the
issue of UN reforms, which was discussed at the 52nd session of
the UN General Assembly, has an important bearing on every member
state.
</P>
<P>
The reforms should not be dictated by a few countries and
should not be allowed to serve only their interests, he
stressed. What is needed is to give democracy free rein, with
extensive discussions conducted on an equal footing, an extensive
airing of all views, particularly those of developing countries,
he said, and the reforms should be acceptable to all member states.
</P>
<P>
The reforms should highlight the role of development in UN
activities, together with that of peace, Li said, noting that they
should help preserve the diversity of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the Security Council should be enlarged
in accordance with the principle of equitable geographical
distribution and should ensure a proper balance between developing
and developed countries so that it will become more representative.
</P>
<P>
Arthur N. Holcombe, resident coordinator of UN Operational
Activities in China, also spoke at the reception, discussing UN's
operations and difficulties as well as the UN-China relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
