<HEADLINE> HK Determined to Deal with Youth Crime and Drug Abuse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government is
determined to deal with the problem of youth crime and drug abuse,
with the support of the community and law enforcement agencies, a
senior official of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(SAR) of China said here today.
</P>
<P>
The SAR's Chief Secretary for Administration Anson Chan, who is
 also chairwoman of the Fight Crime Committee (FCC), told a
reception held today by the FCC that the government will continue
to accord top priority to tackling the problem of youth crime and
steering youths away from crime and drugs.
</P>
<P>
"Although the first nine months of 1997 saw a drop of seven
percent for juvenile offenders (aged between 16 and 20) arrested
for crime when compared with the same period in 1996, we must not
be complacent," Chan said at the reception, which was aimed to
further strengthen the committee's ties with the 18 District Fight
Crime Committees (DFCCs).
</P>
<P>
Chan noted that in the first half of this year, drug abuse for
those aged under 21 was down by 17 percent and she attributed the
drop of youth crime and drug abuses to the constant vigilance by
the excellent police force and the support by the community.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, she said, the government will strengthen police
intelligence and detection capabilities in tackling complex
syndicated and organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will also cooperate with law enforcement agencies and
security forces in the southeastern Chinese province of Guangdong
to tackle increasingly sophisticated trans-boundary crimes.
</P>
<P>
"The district fight crime committees, in particular, have
played a key role in fostering close cooperation between the
police force and the local community in our fight against crime,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank to Borrow for Higher Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines, is planning to borrow 500 million U.S. dollars from
the international capital market in a bid to boost its dollar
reserves and refinance its short-term liabilities, local
television reports said.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the central bank were quoted as saying the bank
was considering an offer from ING bank in Hong Kong, which had
earlier put a 500-million-dollar deposit in the central bank to
increase its foreign reserves.
</P>
<P>
But they said the central bank this time will likely use its
reverse repurchase agreements (RRPs) to back up the loan.
</P>
<P>
RRPs, one effective tool of managing money supply, are
government securities held by the central bank and issued to banks
in exchange for hard currencies with a promise to buy them back in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the Philippine Central Bank Gabriel Singson earlier
confirmed that the bank is contemplating borrowing an initial
tranche of 500 million dollars with five-year to 10-year maturity.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the bank is thinking of raising funds not through
acceptance of deposits, which are short-term in nature, but
through medium-term borrowings.
</P>
<P>
A committee has been tasked to study several proposals from
different investment houses for a possible bond float for the
central bank, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
The gross international reserves (GIR) held by the central bank
reduced sharply to less than 10 billion dollars in July due to the
heavy intervention by the bank in the foreign exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The GIR rose to 10.9 billion dollars as of end-September after
the central bank received about 1 billion dollars in loan from the
International Monetary Fund and other financial bodies.
</P>
<P>
But the GIR dropped anew to 10.5 billion dollars this week
after the central bank stepped in the local currency exchange
again.
</P>
<P>
The GIR refers to foreign exchange denominated assets held by
the central bank such as gold, foreign investments, foreign
currencies and government securities.
</P>
<P>
The central bank wants a higher GIR position since it indicates
the ability of the government to finance its imports and meet its
foreign obligations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
