<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Foreign Trade Volume Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial metropolis, had achieved more than 40 billion US
dollars in its foreign trade volume in the first nine months of
this year, up 15.3 percent from the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
According to Shanghai's customs statistics, in the period,
Shanghai's export volume had a rise of 33 percent to 23.48 billion
US dollars, while its imports went down by 2.9 percent to 16.67
billion US dollars, compared with the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Local state-owned enterprises, which are authorized to export
their products, gained a fast growth in foreign trade this
year. From January to September, their export volume reached 14.17
billion US dollars, making up 60.4 percent of the city's total.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, overseas-funded enterprises have exported 8.65
billion US dollars worth goods, up 36.9 percent from the
corresponding period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the exports of electrical and mechanical products
had gained a dramatic rise of 47.9 percent to top 7.45 billion US
dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
