<TEXT>
<P>
Manila, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Six presidential contenders of
the Philippine ruling Lakas-NUCD party today signed a unity
covenant, vowing to abide by the result of the nomination process
and support a common candidate in the 1998 general elections.
</P>
<P>
But a crack among the party has already emerged as another
presidential aspirant former presidential economic adviser Emilio
"Lito" Osmena failed to attend the signing ceremony held in the
presidential palace this morning.
</P>
<P>
Osmena, who has urged President Fidel Ramos to abandon the
anointment system to keep the party's solidarity, vowed earlier to
run for presidency in the May 1998 national polls with or without
the endorsement of Ramos.
</P>
<P>
Osmena, a founding member of the governing party led by Ramos,
is reportedly planning to join another party as its presidential
bet. A failure to sign the covenant meant Osmena's effective
withdrawal from the nomination contest.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the covenant was designed to prevent the
emergence of another Ramos. During the 1992 national polls, Ramos
failed to be nominated by the then ruling party, but he set up the
Lakas party and won the polls with the endorsement of former
president Corazon Aquino.
</P>
<P>
Among the six signatories were Finance Secretary Roberto de
Ocampo, Speaker of the House of Representatives Jose de Venecia
and former Defense Secretary Renato de Villa.
</P>
<P>
Of them, De Venecia, the party's secretary-general, and De
Villa, a retired general with a similar experience like Ramos,
have been widely viewed as top runners during the contest for
Ramos' endorsement, equal to an estimated 4 million votes.
</P>
<P>
Senator Leticia Ramos-Shahani, Ramos' sister, did not sign the
covenant because she had retreated from the contest and opted to
run for vice president.
</P>
<P>
The administration party will begin a series of nationwide
consultations on November 9 among the party's members gauge their
sentiments on the choice of the party's standard-bearer.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, who will choose his successor based on the results of
the consultations, is expected to announce his choice before
November 27 when the united opposition, the Fight of Patriotic
Filipino Masses party, declared its candidate.
</P>
<P>
The ruling party will hold a national convention in January to
confirm, ratify and officially proclaim Ramos' choice.
</P>
<P>
Ramos, whose single six year term will expire in June 1998, is
ineligible to run for a second term under the country's 1987
constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
