<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0092 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's Water-Drawing Project Goes on Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The project to get water from
the upper reaches of the Huangpu River for Shanghai, the country's
largest industrial city, is going smoothly, according to Municipal
Environmental Protection Bureau officials.
</P>
<P>
It is part of the municipality's drinking-water improvement
project that began in July 1994, that is expected to cost 2.66
billion yuan, with the help of 110 million US dollars in World
Bank loans.
</P>
<P>
The project is designed to supply of 5.4 million cu.m. of water
daily and is scheduled to be completed by 1998. The water will be
supplied to Shanghai water plants through a 40-km channel.
</P>
<P>
The Huangpu River, which is the city's No.1 water resource,
provides an average of 55 billion cubic meters annually, and the
city needs six billion cu.m.
</P>
<P>
The decline in water quality standards in the Huangpu River has
been a major problem for local residents and local industrial and
agricultural production. So, in recent years, Shanghai has adopted
a series of measures to improve its environment, including a
number of waste water treatment projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
