<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Develops Technology to Turn Vegetable Waste </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Indian scientists have
developed an indigenous biochemical technology to recycle
vegetable wastes into bioenergy, a government official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The new technology can not only reduce the mounting garbage
heaps that pollute cities but also leads to the generation of
energy-rich fuel.
</P>
<P>
Vegetable wastes are first solubilized into a slurry, which is
then subjected to fermentation and "anaerobic" digestion in the
presence of methane, producing bacteria which converts the waste
into gas and an effluent.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70 percent of the gas obtained is methane which can be
used as bio-gas fuel. The nutrient rich, odourless effluent can be
used as fertilizer and as an animal feed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
