<HEADLINE> Beijing To Renovate Housing in Muslim District </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Aunt Bai, a Muslim woman who
has lived on Niujie Street in Beijing for most of her life, is
going to fulfill her lifelong dream of living in well-equipped
modern housing, thanks to a new project launched recently by the
municipal government.
</P>
<P>
Niujie Street in central Xuanwu District in southern Beijing is
mainly a Muslim region. More than 30,000 Muslims live along the
street, once important for Islamic activities.
</P>
<P>
The Niujie district long has been a part of the old city
proper. More than 7,500 families have been living here in poor
housing conditions for decades, sparking the municipal government
to give the district a facelift.
</P>
<P>
The renovation project will require 35.91 hectares of land and
300 million yuan (about 36 million US dollars), according to an
executive of the Xuanwu District Real Estate Company. The project,
when finished, will cover an area of 800,000 square meters,
including 370,000 square meters of housing and 430,000 square
meters of public buildings.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 26,000 residents will have to move and 175
enterprises and government agencies will be relocated.
</P>
<P>
"The architectural forms of these buildings will be of Islamic
style, considering the residents' religious passion and ethnic
customs," the executive said. A shopping mall of distinctive
ethnic features will also be built in the district, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
