<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Shares Sharply Rebound After Four-day Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong shares rebounded
largely in closing trade today with a rise of 718.04 points, after
a continuing four-day drop which sent share markets reeling around
the world.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng index, the key indicator of Hong Kong's blue
chips, stood at 11,144.34 points, against Thursday's close of
10,426.30. On Wednesday, the index closed at 11,637. It lost 630
and 567 points on Monday and Tuesday, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Today's sharp rise came after the monetary authorities of the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) took a package of
measures Thursday to fight speculative attacks on the Hong Kong
dollar and to stabilize the local stock market.
</P>
<P>
As the first step, the SAR monetary authorities used foreign
currency reserves to defend the Hong Kong dollar. This forced a
huge rise in interbank interest rates, to 300 percent at one
point, triggering panic selling on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
Then the SAR's biggest firms poured millions of dollars in the
local bourse to buy their own shares.
</P>
<P>
"We have really very good professional management who responded
very quickly to the speculative attacks," Chief Executive of the
SAR Tung Chee Hwa told reporters at the airport earlier today on
his return from his European trip.
</P>
<P>
He said: "The result of that is an increase in interest rate.
And so there is a temporary setback in the stock market, but I
believe this will be short lived."
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the stability of the Hong Kong dollar
lies at the very heart of the SAR's economic stability and the
linked exchange rate is maintained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
