<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close 2 percent Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 24 (Xinhua) - The Australian share market
closed more than two percent down today as stocks reeled from the
impact of falls in European, American and Asian stock markets.
</P>
<P>
By the close of trade a further 6.39 billion U.S. dollars had
been wiped off the market, making a total of around 14 billion
U.S. dollars in just two days.
</P>
<P>
At one stage the all ordinaries plunged as low as 84.5 points
before retreating to close down 53.6 points at 2561.3. It was the
market's lowest close since May 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones broker Stuart Smith said market
bellwether BHP's bullish recovery from a low of 13.46 Australian
dollars to 14.11 Australian dollars at the close helped drive the
semi-recovery.
</P>
<P>
"It shows a certain amount of confidence in the market," Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index plummeted 96.1 points or 2.21 percent
to close at 4257.4 while the all resources finished down 19.2
points or 1.55 percent at 1221.7.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate-sensitive banking sector slumped 159.6 points
or 3.04 percent to 5098.5, with brokers attributing the drop to
the overall market trend and yesterday's wages data which has all
but ruled out a rate cut.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks all closed down with the National Australia Bank
 slipping 55 cents or 2.65 percent to 20.20 Australian dollars on
turnover of 6.3 million shares and the Commonwealth Bank shedding
59.7 cents or 3.63 percent to 15.839 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac fell 25.3 cents or 2.88 percent to 8.53 Australian
dollars on heavy turnover of 7.4 million shares, Macquarie Bank
slipped 44.3 cents or 3.63 percent to finish at 7.56 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
ANZ lost 45 cents or 4.32 percent to 9.96 Australian dollars
with 9.4 million shares traded.
</P>
<P>
Among other leading industrials Lend Lease dropped 1.09
Australian dollars to close at 30.10 Australian dollars and Coca
Cola Amatil slipped 35 cents to 11.50 Australian dollars while
Brambles defied the market fall to gain 30.4 cents to close at
27.61 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Insurance and financial services giant National Mutual Holdings
topped the index of most heavily traded stocks with 18.913 million
shares changing hands worth 30.09 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National Mutual shares lost 10.1 cents to close at 2.25
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The company's National Mutual Asia division is the only
Australian entity listed on the Hong Kong stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
Among resources stocks, profit taking lifted BHP 11.1 cents or
0.79 percent to 14.11 Australian dollars on heavy turnover of 12.1
million shares.
</P>
<P>
Global miner Rio Tinto shed 54 cents or 2.82 percent to 18.61
Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 27 points to 1249.4, off an earlier low of
1232.2.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 456.80 million shares worth 1.055 billion
U.S. dollars, with rises of 435 outnumbering falls of 65.
</P>
</TEXT>
