<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Raises Interest Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Macao banks raised interest rates
by 0.75-0.95 percent today following a similar move in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Macao Daily News reported today that after the announcement
of interest rates rise in Hong Kong on Thursday as a way to
maintain the exchange rate of Hong Kong dollar, most Macao bankers
decided to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
They began to add 0.75 percent to 0.95 percent to the original
preferential interest rates today. Whether bank deposit interest
rates will be raised is to be decided by bankers later today.
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, many local banks have raised their
interest rates for fixed deposits of one to three months by about
1 percent. The rates now stand at 7-8 percent for one to three
month fixed deposits.
</P>
<P>
Local financiers said that the higher interest rates may last
quite some time, adding that further lifting of rates is possible.
</P>
<P>
The rates rise means a blow to the real estate business, which
has been slowly recovering after an over-two-year slump, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vitor Pessoa, secretary for economy and
coordination, said that the Macao currency, pataca, will remain
pegged to the Hong Kong dollar to avoid possible fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
One Hong Kong dollar equals to about 1.03 patacas at present.
The local currency is now connected with the U.S. dollar indirectly
via the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
He said the Macao currency will remain stable so long as it is
pegged to the Hong Kong dollar, adding that the pataca is not a
possible target of speculators as Macao is only a tiny place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
