<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Hits New Low as Hang Seng Tumbles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar today
plunged below 70 U.S. cents to a level not seen since January
1994, reacting to the fall in Hong Kong's Hang Seng index and the
potential fall-out for related economies.
</P>
<P>
Overnight the Australian dollar received a hammering from
offshore investors, plummeting to 69.75 U.S. cents, a new
three-year low.
</P>
<P>
However during trading over the day, the local currency jumped
nearly one U.S. cent higher to close just a little weaker on the
day.
</P>
<P>
Traders said heavy buying by U.S. funds short of Australian
dollars as well as partial retracements of the main stock index in
the Hong Kong share market helped the unit recover.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 70.58 U.S. cents, from 70.68
U.S. cents locally late yesterday.
</P>
<P>
Traders breathed a sigh of relief as the currency took on a
more positive hue following the wide price dips of the past three
sessions sparked by the currency and economic crisis in South East
Asia.
</P>
<P>
At close tonight, the Australian dollar was at 85.45 yen from
85.89 yesterday, and against the Deutsch mark it was at 1.2531,
from 1.2639.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
