<HEADLINE> Share Prices Continue to Decline on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Share prices continued to
decline on the Singapore market as the benchmark Straits Times
Industrials Index (STII) lost another 32.06 points to close at
1617.81 points today.
</P>
<P>
The STII nose-dived by 69.99 points one hour after opening to
1579.88 points, breaking the 1600-point level to record an
all-time low in about five years. The market rallied later with
the STII reaching the day's high of 1652.84 points before it fell
again in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 263.86 million units, worth
666.14 million Singapore dollars (about 421.61 million US
dollars). Declines led advances by 196 to 147, while 261 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Local computer maker IPC Corporation was the most actively
traded stock as it registered a turnover of 14.83 million units.
It was followed by Hong Kong Land warrant97 which had 11.92
million units traded. The DBS (Development Bank of Singapore) Land
was next with 11.48 million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Creative 50 led the gainers of the day as it rose by 1.3
dollars to finish at 40.6 Singapore dollars. Elec increased by 80
cents to end at 6.7 US dollars, while Kuala Lumpur Kepong gained
38 cents to close at 3.6 dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Bukit Sembawang was the biggest loser as it
declined by 1.5 dollars to end at 13.8 Singapore dollars. The
Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign fell by 90 cents to close
at 20.1 Singapore dollars. Venture Warrant9907 lost 85 cents to
finish at 4.3 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
