<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Exports Up 12.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Macao's exports in the first
eight months of the year reached 11.3 billion patacas (about 1.43
billion US dollars), up 12.2 percent from the same period last
year.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics Department
show that Macao has gained a first trade surplus of 174 million
patacas (about 22 million US dollars) in two years.
</P>
<P>
The export value of textiles and clothing accounted for
85.1 percent of all exports, showing a 19.9 percent increase from
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The export of non-textile products dropped 5.5 percent. They
include machinery, equipment, footwear and cement.
</P>
<P>
Most of the exports went to the United States and the European
Union nations, which bought 77.6 percent of Macao's export
goods. Exports to the two markets ship up some 20 percent from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports in the first eight months rose 6.8 percent
to reach 11.2 billion patacas (about 1.42 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Of all imported goods, capital goods surged 18.2 percent, raw
materials and semi-finished goods climbed eight percent, and fuel
and lubricative oil jumped nine percent. But imports of consumer
goods edged down 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Macao bought 80.3 percent of imported goods from the
Asia-Pacific region. While goods from China's inland, Taiwan and
Japan increased, those from Hong Kong, Australia and the Republic
of Korea declined.
</P>
<P>
Local observers say that the brisk business of foreign trade, a
mainstay of Macao's economy, indicates that its economy is on a
recovery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese President Says Overseas Intellectual Resources Important </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- President Jiang Zemin said
today that China places a great deal of importance on overseas
intellectual resources and has been active in using these
resources.
</P>
<P>
He was speaking at the final day of the Third
Sino-U.S. Technology and Engineering Conference in Beijing's Great
Hall of the Peop1e, where he told participants that learning from
foreign countries' advanced technology and management techniques
as well as other achievements of their civilization to speed up
China's development is an important part of its opening up drive.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said the foreign experts have made many good suggestions
on improving engineering technology and management in China,s
enterprises during the conferences, and have helped promote
Sino-U.S. exchanges and co-operation. These experiences should be
summarized and new areas and channels of co-operation be opened,
he said.
</P>
<P>
talented personnel are one of the most important resources in
scientific and technological progress and social and economic
development, and intellectual resources are needed to increase
knowledge. China's reform and modernization drive needs large
numbers of outstanding intellectuals who have the pioneering and
creative spirit, but who are also good at learning from others,
Jiang emphasized. This is the major intellectual backing of the
country's socialist cause, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called on departments in charge of foreign experts work
to provide better working and living conditions for those working
in China and encourage them to make full use of their
talent. Their intellectual property rights and other rights must
also be protected in keeping with China's law and international
practices, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
The five-day conference focused on solving engineering and
technological problems and using domestic and external resources
to promote technical innovation in enterprises. 
</P>
</TEXT>
