<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Kuan Yew Calls For Stronger US-ASEAN Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister Lee
Kuan Yew called for a stronger link between the United States and
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) countries,
which he said will benefit both sides.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the Fortune 500 Forum in Boston, which was
also distributed here today, Lee Kuan Yew said that a stronger
U.S.-ASEAN linkage will ensure that there will be no major
East-West divide down the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Such a split, he warned, could come about if the United States
were to have free trade agreements or FTAs only with the Americas
at a time when East Asian countries were growing fast and
increasing trade between themselves.
</P>
<P>
He hopes to see the U.S. conclude FTAs with the ASEAN countries
to provide the framework to develop deep and broad economic links.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the currency turmoil in Southeast Asia, Lee said the
governments need to be disciplined in their macroeconomic policies
to win back investors' confidence.
</P>
<P>
He is confident that those governments that have the political
strength to do the unpleasant quickly and thoroughly will reap the
best rewards.  
</P>
</TEXT>
