<HEADLINE> Japan to Send Mission to DPRK in Mid-November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) and its two noncabinet allies, today formally accepted
an invitation by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
to send a mission there in mid-November, according to a Kyodo News
report.
</P>
<P>
Yoshiro Mori, chairman of the LDP's General Council, conveyed
the acceptance of the invitation from the governing Workers Party
of Korea Residents in Japan (Chongryun), a pro-Pyongyang
organization, Kyodo quoted LDP officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
Mori, who will head the mission, requested the arrangement of a
meeting with DPRK leader Kim Jong Il during the visit, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to meet many people from various fields for frank
talks in order to set the environment for furthering negotiations
aimed at normalizing diplomatic ties with the DPRK," Mori was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The delegation will consist of five legislators from the LDP,
three from the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and one from New
Party Sakigake, and plans a four-day visit to Pyongyang, Mori
told the Chongryun executive.
</P>
<P>
The executive replied, "we welcome the visit with great
expectations now we have only three years ahead toward the 21st
Century."
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate the eagerness expressed by Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto and Foreign Minister Keizo Obuchi to improve
Japan-DPRK relations," the executive added. 
</P>
