<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Military Denies Selling Human Organs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese military
officer today denied a US television report that some People's
Liberation Army (PLA) hospitals are selling the organs of convicts
who are sentenced to death, calling the ABC documentary a "pure
fabrication".
</P>
<P>
A thorough investigation has shown that the footages used in
the documentary, with the exception of a few shots of entrances to
medical centers in south China that are open to foreigners, are
"fabrications" that have nothing to do with PLA hospitals.
</P>
<P>
"Surgeons appearing in the documentary are not PLA medical
personnel and the evidence they presented in no way conforms to
reality," the officer said, pointing out that Henry Wu, who
participated in the plot, made up similar stories two years ago.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, he and a BBC reporter made a TV documentary about
China in which they showed some tombs and described them as tombs
of convicts sentenced to death. But the inscriptions on the
tombstone indicated that they were graves of departed local
residents.
</P>
<P>
They pretended to be a husband and wife team and shot footage
of a heart surgery during a visit to a Chinese hospital, then
claimed it was an organ transplant operation using an organ taken
from an executed convict.
</P>
<P>
Wu later admitted that he had been asked to help make an
anti-Chinese documentary and made it by substituting some scenes
for others.
</P>
<P>
The PLA officer pointed out that the Chinese government
strictly bans the sale of human organs, and, as is the case
elsewhere, a very few PLA hospitals that have approval, can do
organ transplants.
</P>
<P>
These are done in accordance with the law and the organs are
donated voluntarily and handled according to special procedures.
</P>
<P>
"There has never been a single case involving the sale of
organs of executed convicts," the officer stated, and pointed out
that ABC was using a lie at a time when relations between China
and the United States are showing signs of improvement, but that
anyone with a good sense can see their real intention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, October 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones industrial average tumbled almost 200
points Thursday as a big selloff in Hong Kong influenced other
major markets, triggering a global stock slide.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, an index of 30 multinational companies whose profits
have already been pinched by the mounting economic turmoil in
Southeast Asia, fell 186.88 to 7,847.77.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also sank by about 2 percent, slightly
less than the 2.3 percent loss suffered by the Dow, which still
boasts a 21.7 percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's main stock index plunged 10 percent Thursday. (New
York, Stocks Plunge)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- Despite good harvests in recent years in China,
this country is prepared to buy wheat from the United States, as a
way of reducing trade deficit on the U.S. side, a high ranking
Chinese official announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Economic and Trade Delegation is going to make
an order for the commodity with an amount of 700,000 tons,
delegation head and Vice Chairman of the State Planning Commission
Zeng Peiyan said in an interview with Xinhua and local
media. (U.S.-China-Economic Ties)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW YORK -- The visiting Chinese trade delegation witnessed
here Thursday another expensive signing in which the Shanghai GM
will purchase vehicle component sets worth 200 million
U.S. dollars from General Motors Corporation (GM).
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai GM is partly a baby company of GM, the largest
auto maker in the world. It is an equally divided joint venture
launched formally in June this year in the booming Pudong New Area
of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for General Motors to export up to 18,000
component sets for a Buick mid-luxury car and its derivatives to
support pre-launch and start-up activities. (New York-GM
Purchasing)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
EDINBURGH -- The 31st Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting
will be held in Edinburgh from October 24, with the focus on
promoting closer economic and trade cooperation among the 54
Commonwealth countries.
</P>
<P>
During the four-day meeting, the Commonwealth leaders are
expected to discuss the particular theme of "Trade, Investment and
Development: The Road to Commonwealth
Prosperity". (UK-Commonwealth)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Russia has offered to supply natural gas to parts
of northern India through a pipeline from Siberia, a government
official said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Russian First Deputy Minister for Fuel and Energy Vitali
V. Bushuev made the offer during the ongoing fourth Indo-Russian
Joint Working Group Meeting on power here.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Bushuev expressed his country's willingness to
supply natural gas to India and set up a long-distance
transmission line from major generating sources in
Siberia. (India-Russia-Gas)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- The summit of the Commonwealth of Independent States
(CIS) concluded Thursday in Chisinau, capital of Moldova, without
any resolutions being adopted.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after the one-day meeting, Russian
President Boris Yeltsin said the CIS must be kept and
strengthened. He said the CIS would always
exist. (CIS-Summit-Russia)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec Thursday
resigned unexpectedly, saying that he found it difficult to carry
out his duties.
</P>
<P>
President Vaclav Havel accepted Zieleniec's resignation after
consulting with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus.
</P>
<P>
Zieleniec, 51, who has been the foreign minister since January
1993, told a news conference that he was also quitting as deputy
chairman of the ruling Civic Democratic Party (ODS) headed by
Klaus. (Czech Republic-FM-Resignation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
