<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johannesburg Stock Tumbles After Hong Kong Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Johannesburg
Stock Exchange (JSE) Thursday suffered its biggest one-day loss in six
years after a 10 percent crash in Hong Kong's stock market, local
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
The JSE all share index lost 326 points or 4.4 percent to 7,094.2,
the biggest percentage fall since August 1991. It was four point short
of the 330-point fall in the wake of the "Black Monday" crash on Wall
Street in October 1987.
</P>
<P>
Industrial stocks fell 355 points or 3.9 percent to 8,682, while
the financial index shed 467 points or 4.4 percent to 10,201.2.
</P>
<P>
The fall wiped almost 10 billion Rand (2.1 billion U.S. dollars)
off the market capitalization of the JSE's two largest stocks, De
Beers and Anglo American Corporation. De Beers's 15.20 Rand (3.2
dollars) loss to 124.60 (26.5 dollars) was sparked by fears that the
Asian crisis would dampen that region's hunger for diamonds, dragging
associate Anglo American down 17.20 Rand (3.7 dollars) to 235.40 Rand
(50 dollars).
</P>
<P>
De Beers is the world's largest diamond company.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong crisis also sparked a heavy losses in the South
African futures market, where a record 3.7 billion Rand (800 million
dollar) worth of futures contracts changed hands.
</P>
<P>
South Africa's bond market came under attack as foreign investors
lost their appetite for emerging markets in the wake of the turbulence
in the east.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Hang Seng index shed 10 percent to close at 10,426 on
interest rate hikes sparked by a speculative attack on its currency.
</P>
<P>
The crash caused panic in other Asian markets and had repercussions
in Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Markets in Indonesia, Taiwan, the Philippines and Malaysia recorded
losses ranging from 1.7 to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Europe, exchanges in France and Britain fell by more than 3
percent and Germany's DAX lost 4.66 percent. In the United States, the
Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 186.88 points to 7,847.77 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
