<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Porcelain Ware to Be Shown in Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Many delicate pieces of porcelain
ware from Yaozhou Kiln in Shaanxi province in northwest China will
be on display in Japan on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Yaozhou Kiln porcelain was given as tributes to the emperors in
the Tang and Song dynasties and was important in the history of
porcelain production in China.
</P>
<P>
Many important pieces of three-colored glazed porcelain have
been found at ancient sites in Kyoto and other Japanese cities.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition in Japan will have 114 pieces of porcelain ware
on display, including many national treasures like a black covered
jar, a celadon piece with incised flower design, a porcelain vase
with interlocking branch and leaf design, and a white glazed
three-legged burner with incised flower design.
</P>
<P>
This is the second overseas show of Chinese porcelain
relics. The first was organized by Jiangxi Province's Jingdezhen
city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
