<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Date Set for Goldenberg Corruption Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Goldenberg corruption
case, which has been cited by the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) as the biggest obstacle for resumption of its huge loan to
Kenya, will be heard on a daily basis from December 3.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Attorney-General Amos Wako, when declaring the date
Thursday, denied any delay intention by the government.
</P>
<P>
"A case of this magnitude, even in the United Kingdom, does
not take less than six or seven years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Golderberg scandal exposed a series of deals which caused
the loss of more than 12 billion Shillings (some 200 million U.S.
Dollars) in the form of export compensation.
</P>
<P>
The accused in the case are famous tycoon Kamlesh Pattni,
former Treasury Permanent Secretary Wilfred Koinange, former
Central Bank Deputy Governor Eliphaz Riungu and his colleague
Michael Wanjihia Onesmus.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, IMF announced the suspension of a 205-million-Dollar
key aid package to Kenya, blaming the Kenyan government for
failing to take enough measures to set up financial
accountability with the Goldenberg scandal as the most serious
sample.
</P>
<P>
Defense lawyers then took advantage of IMF remarks to claim a
mistrial, noting the IMF had prejudiced the case by sending out a
clear message that anything short of a conviction of the accused
would mean no aid would be forthcoming to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
However, Nairobi Chief Magistrate Uniter Pamella Kidullah has
dismissed the application to terminate the hearing of the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0137 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Modern Norway" Seminar Held in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A seminar on "Modern Norway"
co-sponsored by the Development Research Center under the State
Council and the Norwegian Embassy in Beijing was held here today.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 participants from the two countries were briefed
on Norwegian society -- the role of its press and media, equality
and Norway's mixed economy.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Norwegian King Harald V and Chinese State Councillor
Li Guixian attended the opening ceremony and delivered speeches.
</P>
<P>
Harald V briefly explained Norwegian society, politics and
economy, and said that the seminar would enable the two sides to
exchange opinions and share Norway's experience in its transition
period.
</P>
<P>
Li said Norway is one of the earliest western countries to
establish diplomatic ties with China, and there is a firm basis
for bilateral friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
Entering the 1990s, Li said, Sino-Norwegian relations have
further improved and developed, and the growth of bilateral
economic and trade cooperation is especially noticeable with
bilateral trade volume in the first half of this year up 133
percent compared with the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
He cited the great potential and promising prospects for
bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The experience of Norway's mixed-market economy and social
insurance system has drawn the interest of Chinese economists and
researchers, Li said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that this seminar will make positive
contributions to Sino-Norwegian mutual understanding.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Sees Steady Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese capital expects to
reach all economic goals this year, as the latest Beijing
Statistics Bureau figures show steady economic growth in the
first three quarters.
</P>
<P>
From January to September, its GDP was 123.3 billion yuan (14.8
billion US dollars), up 10 percent from the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
The industrial sector reported over six billion yuan in pre-tax
profits, and losses by state-owned businesses were down.
</P>
<P>
Beijing brought in 1.68 billion US dollars in overseas
investment for the first three quarters, 1.17 billion dollars of
which was direct overseas investment. The two figures were
slightly lower than those for the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Inflation was 3.3 percentage points lower than last year's 7.3
percent, meaning high growth with low inflation.  
</P>
</TEXT>
