<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xiamen Attracts More Overseas Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Xiamen, a special economic
zone in eastern China's Fujian Province, has become attractive
for overseas investors because of its favorable natural
conditions, International Business Daily has reported.
</P>
<P>
More than 4,140 overseas-funded projects have been approved
through August, with a total contractual investment of 12.95
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The investors come from 25 countries and regions. The principal
industries include electronics, chemicals and
machine-building. Xiamen also attracted high-tech enterprises from
overseas.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Citibank of North America and Mitsubishi of Japan
have opened representative offices in Xiamen. Negotiations
have begun with Boeing, Kodak and General Motors.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 3,200 overseas-funded enterprises have begun
operation, introducing advanced technology and expertise as well
as providing employment opportunities and increasing tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that the industrial output of overseas-funded
enterprises exceeded 18.7 billion U.S. dollars during the first
six months of this year, accounting for 78.7 percent of the city's
total.
</P>
<P>
The overseas-funded enterprises have been playing an important
role in promoting the city's economic growth, the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
Xiamen, separated only by the Taiwan Straits, has attracted
1,500 Taiwan-funded enterprises with a total investment of 3.25
billion U.S. dollars. The city has become important to Taiwan's
economy.
</P>
<P>
Sixty investment ventures were added between January and August
with a contractual amount of 245 million U.S. dollars, 23.5
percent more than the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
