<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Berger Describes U.S.-China Summit As Milestone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. official said
here today that the summit next week between Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton will be a "milestone".
</P>
<P>
"I have said to our people in preparation for the summit that
we should consider the summit to be a milestone, but not a
millstone," Sandy Berger, Clinton's national security assistant,
told a White House briefing.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the summit is a milestone "in the sense that
we can use the summit to try to make progress on a number of
areas, but we ought not to see the summit as an artificial
deadline."
</P>
<P>
The week-long state visit by Jiang to the United States, which
starts on October 26, will be the first one ever paid by a Chinese
head of state since 1985.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will discuss their "strategic relationship,"
cooperation in keeping stability and peace and issues concerning
security and economy, Berger said.
</P>
<P>
Berger thought that regular summits between the United States
and China are generally a good thing.
</P>
<P>
The United States does not seek to contain China or treat China
as enemy, said the assistant. "We want to engage with China to
expand areas of cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Berger said the United States shares "a very wide-range of
interests" with China, stressing that the differences between the
two countries should be handled in a "face to face" way and the
summit should not be seen as an artificial deadline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
