<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Once Exhausted Fishery Rejuvenated in Zhejiang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Zhoushan Fishery in
eastern China's Zhejiang Province has been revived by the rapid
growth of deep-water fishing and the commercial fish-breeding
industries.
</P>
<P>
Located on the East China Sea, Zhoushan has a marine
area of more than 20,000 square kilometers, the largest in China
and one of the world's top four fisheries.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Zhoushan's aquatic output topped 1.05 million tons,
twice the figure in 1990, and accounted for 10 percent of the
country's total.
</P>
<P>
When fishing season comes, hundreds of thousands of fishing
boats converge around Zhoushan from other coastal provinces of
China, even from other countries.
</P>
<P>
However, due to over-fishing in the 1970s and 1980s, the
Zhoushan Fishery showed signs of resources depletion in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
The government in Zhoushan City then decided to control
inshore fishing and promote the development of deep-sea fishing
and fish-breeding.
</P>
<P>
Zhoushan now has long-term cooperative agreements with fishing
organizations in more than 30 countries, including Japan,
Australia, the Republic of Korea and Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the city's fishing fleet brought back a catch of
100,000 tons of deep-water fish and its output from breeding
amounted to 30,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Local fishermen have obtained an awareness that the costing
deep-water fishing requires cooperation with overseas investors
and the introduction of compensated trade.
</P>
<P>
Apart from tapping marine resources, the city in recent years
has focused on protecting the marine ecology. For the past two
years, millions of shrimp, groupers and jellyfish have been
planted each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cholera Under Control in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The cholera epidemic, which
killed more than 200 in Kenya's southwestern province of Nyanza
in the past three months, has been put under control, a Kenyan
health official said.
</P>
<P>
No cholera-related deaths had been reported within the past 24
hours, an indication that the disease had been controlled, said
Daily Nation newspaper today quoting Provincial Medical Officer
Richard Otieno Muga.
</P>
<P>
"Reports reaching me from the affected areas indicate that the
situation is getting better but I am urging medical officers
involved in the campaign not to slacken because we cannot rule
out chances of a re-emergence of the disease," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kisumu District Hospital, which teemed with cholera
victims last week, had only four victims by Thursday, he added.
</P>
<P>
The number of cholera patients at the Homa Bay District
Hospital had reduced from 46 to 28 within two days. Homa Bay and
Kisumu are among the worst-hit areas by cholera.
</P>
<P>
"Other areas like Muhoroni and Ahero have also reported few
admissions following a massive campaign," Muga said.
</P>
<P>
He assured the public that drugs had been supplied to all
health centers in the affected areas and called on them to report
to the institutions immediately they developed cholera symptoms.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the public must also continue to maintain high
standards of hygiene and disposal of waste must never be taken
for granted again," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kisumu District Hospital's medical superintendent, George
Ogonji, said the hospital had discharged most cholera patients
and had dispatched medical personnel to treat their relatives to
prevent fresh outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry declared an all-out war against cholera
last week and offered fresh supplies of drugs worth nine million
Kenyan Shillings (about 150,000 U.S. Dollars) Saturday in Kisumu,
the third-largest city in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Health officials also launched public health campaign to
improve hygienic standards in the affected areas.
</P>
<P>
However, given the forecast of upcoming rains in the next two
weeks, top medical officials warned that the rains which have
been pounding some parts of Nyanza Province could exacerbate the
cholera situation in the lowland areas of the regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
