<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Renovating Classical Government Office In Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Henan
Province will renovate a 600-year-old government office in Yexian
County, local officials say.
</P>
<P>
The county government office compound was built in 1369 and is
still standing even after several hundred years of warfare. Most
of the 53 rooms in the 12,000-sq.m. space are still intact.
</P>
<P>
The building is the sole survivor of the North China
architectural tradition of the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644).
</P>
<P>
Because the large-scale renovation that was needed in recent
decades wasn't done, many structures decayed and collapsed. To
preserve the cultural site, local relics protection organizations
decided on the restoration project to use it as a museum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
