<HEADLINE> Chinese, Djiboutian Foreign Ministers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen held talks with Mouhanmed Moussa
Chehem, minister of foreign affairs and international cooperation
of the Republic of Djibouti, at the Diaoyutai State Guest House
here today.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that friendly cooperative relations between the two
countries have been developing smoothly since they established
diplomatic ties 18 years ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that cooperation between the two countries have
achieved satisfactory results. He noted that in recent years,
personnel exchanges have been increased and fields of cooperation
expanded.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the Chinese government treasures friendship between
the two countries and is ready to work with the Djiboutian
government to consolidate and develop long-term stable relations
in accordance with the principles of equal treatment, true
friendship, unity and cooperation, and seeking common development.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he appreciated the Djiboutian government for its
adherence to the "one China" stance.
</P>
<P>
In turn, Chehem praised China for its achievements in economic
growth and thanked the Chinese for their assistance to his
country. He reiterated that his government recognizes that the
Government of the People's Republic of China is the sole
legitimate government that represents the whole China. He said
Djibouti supports the cause of reunification of China.
</P>
<P>
He also briefed Qian about the situation in the Horn of Africa
and Somalia.
</P>
<P>
Qian said the only way out of the problem in Somalia is to
reconcile the various ethnic groups. He said he hopes all parties
in Somalia will put national interests and the people's interests
above everything else and resolve conflicts through negotiation
and dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He also said that China supports and appreciates countries in
the Horn of Africa for their efforts to promote regional peace and
stability, resolve their disputes peacefully, mediate conflicts
among all parties in Somalia and rehabilitate and develop their
economies.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also exchanged views on issues of
Africa and others of common concern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
