<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-15 Trade Ministers to Discuss WTO-Related Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Trade and economic
ministers of the Group of 15 (G-15) developing countries will meet
here on October 31 to discuss issues related to the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Malaysian International Trade and Industry
Minister Rafidah Aziz said today.
</P>
<P>
The issues include the implementation of WTO obligations and
on-going work on the built-in agenda, she told a briefing on the
G-15 trade and economic ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
"We will also review the status of the discussions being
undertaken by the various WTO Working Groups in the areas of trade
and investment, competition policy as well as transparency in
government procurement," she said.
</P>
<P>
The ministers' meeting, ahead of the G-15 leaders' summit on
November 3-5 here, will seek possible joint approaches in dealing
with multilateral trade issues ahead of the WTO Ministerial
Meeting in Geneva in May next year, she said.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 members at the pervious WTO Ministerial Meeting in
Singapore in 1996 agreed to reject extraneous issues in the WTO
such as the social clause and labor standards. They were also
united in the principle of progressive liberalization based on the
level of development.
</P>
<P>
The meeting next week would reinforce the common stance,
Rafidah said, adding that WTO Director General Renarto Ruggiero
would have a dialogue with the G-15 ministers to update them on
what is happening in the WTO.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Secretary General of the United Nations Conference on
Trade and Development (UNCTAD) Carlos Fortini is also scheduled to
have a dialogue with the ministers, she said.
</P>
<P>
Besides reviewing developments in the multilateral trading
system, the G-15 ministers would also focus on G-15 members'
cooperation in trade and investment and possible private sector
participation in the group, she said.
</P>
<P>
She added that the ministers would discuss trade and investment
facilitation measures such as information exchange, mobility of
business people and technical cooperation.
</P>
<P>
According to Rafidah, the G-15 ministerial meeting would be
independent of the leaders' summit.
</P>
<P>
The G-15 spans three continents and the present members are
Algeria, Argentina, Brazil, Chile, Egypt, India, Indonesia,
Jamaica, Malaysia, Mexico, Nigeria, Peru, Senegal, Venezuela and
Zimbabwe. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
