The senior officers were drawn from Zimbabwe, Mauritius, South
Africa, Namibia, Lesotho, Malawi, Tanzania and Botswana.
</P>
<P>
They had been on a two-week peacekeeping course in Harare, and
went to Nyanga Thursday for their last practical lessons.
</P>
<P>
As part of the southern African regional peacekeeping efforts,
Zimbabwe was mandated in 1995 to coordinate peacekeeping training
courses for military and non-military personnel in preparation
for deployment to conflict areas.
</P>
<P>
The first regional peacekeeping commanders' course was held in
1995, with the second one last year and the third being the one
which ends today.
</P>
<P>
Commandant of the Zimbabwe Staff College Brigadier Hapton
Bonyongwe said the aim of the course, which started on October
13, was to teach senior officers the theory and practice of peace
support operations sponsored by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Salim Ahmed Salim, secretary-general of the Organization of
African Unity, will officially close the course code-named
"Operation Blue Rhino", in Harare today.
</P>
<P>
Course Director Colonel Richman Ncube said the intention was
to expose the senior officers to situations they were likely to
encounter when on peace keeping missions.
</P>
<P>
"While on peace missions," he said, "the soldiers must avoid a
situation in which they find themselves as part of the problem
instead of being a means to a solution."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
