<BODY>
<HEADLINE> England's World Cup Proposal Meets Setback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- FIFA general secretary Sepp
Blatter said on Friday that the ideal of hosting matches in Wales
and Scotland, which is included in the plan of England's bid for
the 2006 World Cup, would be evaluated by the world ruling body.
</P>
<P>
According to the FIFA regulations, the host country should
stage all matches within its borders. And England, Scotland, Wales
and Northern Ireland are four independent ruling bodies of FIFA.
</P>
<P>
So a match in Glasgow or Wales would be outside the area
controlled by England's Football Association.
</P>
<P>
Blatter said lawyers would evaluated the proposal, if it was
included in England's bid, to determine whether it violated FIFA
rules for staging the 32-team tournament.
</P>
<P>
Besides England, Germany, South Africa, Morocco, Argentina and
Brazil are also in the bid roster. The official bid plan must be
submitted in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
