<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Customs Office Helps Develop Export-Led Economy in Shanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Local customs officials in
northern Shanxi Province have played a big role in promoting the
development of an export-oriented economy in this land-locked
province, one of the major energy producers in China.
</P>
<P>
Since it opened in 1987, the Taiyuan Customs Office has helped
the province develop economic ties with other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
The customs office has taken measures to lower the cost of
imports and exports for local enterprises, also an inducement for
foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
These efforts have paid off. To date, Shanxi has established
trade ties with 100 foreign countries and regions. In 1996, Shanxi
handled 1.21 billion U.S. dollars in imports and exports, nearly
six times the total for 1987.
</P>
<P>
The province now has 1,500 overseas-funded enterprises, with a
total investment of nearly two billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the province's export and import processing was
valued at 240 million U.S. dollars, one-fifth of its total foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
Local products selling well abroad include minerals, metals,
rolled steel, electronic and mechanical products, chemicals and
textiles.
</P>
<P>
With the help of customs officials, the province has begun
direct charter passenger flights to Hong Kong and charter cargo
flights to Russia.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, when the Taiyuan Port of Entry opened, customs made
further efforts to simplify the clearance procedure to make
imports and exports more efficient. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
