<HEADLINE> European Shares Plunge on Asian Market Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all extended Wednesday's losses and ended sharply lower as
shockwaves from Hong Kong's plunge rocked the markets.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index had dropped 222 points at one stage
early today before closing at 4,991.50 points, down 3.06 percent
or 157.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that Wall Street's relative stability in the face
of global stock market turmoil saved London prices from disaster.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that market movements were also exaggerated by the
new SETs trading system the London market adopted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 28 billion pounds (45.7 billion
US dollars) were wiped off the value of UK's leading stock index
and shares of companies that do business in Asia were among the
hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Shares prices in Frankfurt also slid, with the DAX-30 index
closing at 3,977.26, down 194.19 points or 4.66 percent, once
again below the key 4,000-point level, as the plunge in Hong Kong
hurt sentiment.
</P>
<P>
A trader said that "while there is no real reason for us to
react so strongly to what goes on in Southeast Asia, the losses
are having a psychological influence".
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index followed the whole world and ended
101.19 points lower at 2,856.87. 
</P>
</TEXT>
