<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Searching for New Habitats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chilai Doje, a 58-year-old
Tibetan farmer, has begun a new life with his family in Gama
Gyitang, a village on Yarlung Zangbo River in Tibet Autonomous
Region. Six years ago Gama Gyitang was barren land, covered by
stones and overgrown with weeds.
</P>
<P>
Doje said about 30 families of Tibetan farmers or herdsmen now
live at the village as part of a poverty-relief project launched
by the local government of Gyaca County.
</P>
<P>
With an investment of more than 1 million yuan (about 120,000
U.S. dollars), the local government of Gyaca has brought some 467
hectares of land under cultivation and relocated more than 1,000
Tibetans from remote mountains to flat land with rich soil.
</P>
<P>
Doje said he was uneasy at first after moving out of the
mountains, but that he now approves of the project.
</P>
<P>
"We now have enough food and fresh vegetables," he said.
</P>
<P>
Doje and his family farm on 1.5 hectares of land designated by
the local government. They plant crops such as highland barley and
wheat, and vegetables such as hot peppers, cabbage and garlic.
</P>
<P>
This year they have reaped 2,500 kilograms of grain and raised
70 head of cattles and goats.
</P>
<P>
"There is only a little land for farming in the mountains with
no irrigation system. In the past we often had to live on state
relief funds when the harvest was poor due to natural disaster,"
Doje said.
</P>
<P>
Soinam Chagba, Doje's neighbor, is also satisfied with the
quality of life after migration.
</P>
<P>
"The living conditions here are far better than that in the
mountains," she said. "Besides the high-grain-yielding rich soil,
the nearby road also provides us convenient transportation."
</P>
<P>
Chagba and her husband are making money by trading in local
products and raising herds. They plan to move into a new house
this year.
</P>
<P>
With 1,500 hectares of farmland and a population of 17,000,
Gyaca long has been one of the 18 most impoverished counties in
Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to the comprehensive economic standards released by
the regional government, the village has risen above the poverty
level. Another 1,000 Tibetans are expected to emigrate from the
mountains, according to local sources. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EPA Agrees to Bury Nuke Waste in New Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Environment Protection
Agency(EPA) today preliminarily agreed with a plan to bury nuclear
waste in Southeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The decision sets the stage for the so-called Waste Isolation
Pilot Plant, completed in 1988 at a cost of 1.8 billion U.S.
dollars, to open after two decades of heated debate.
</P>
<P>
The EPA said the final ruling will be made public next Spring
and the public has four months to comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have raised questions over many years about
the safety of the repository, such as curently drilling in the
area and hauling radioactive waste hundedss of miles to the
repository.
</P>
<P>
According to reports coming from New Mexico, the EPA promised
the respository would prevent human radiation doses higher than
the equivalenty of about 2 chest X-rays per year, and markers
would be placed around the site to discourage future generations
from mining or drilling in the area.
</P>
<P>
The repository would receive about 37,700 waste shipments over
the next 35 years. The waste shipments would largely come from
defense industry in 10 states, including California, Colorado,
Idahoalenty, Illinois, Nevada and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered a part of a strategy for cleaning up
government nuclear wast sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
