<HEADLINE> Greece Comes to Standstill Due to General Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Greece was almost brought to a
standstill today as a 24-hour general strike nationwide was called
by the General Confederation of Greek Workers (GSEE), the largest
labour union in the country.
</P>
<P>
Striking workers throughout the country held rallies and
marched to the streets in demand for higher wages, a 35-hour
working hour and no cuts in social security benefits.
</P>
<P>
Banks and many shops remained closed all day while transport
were disrupted for several hours due to stoppages.
</P>
<P>
Ministries closed down for several hours as the civil servants
union staged a four-hour stoppage in support of the GSEE strike.
</P>
<P>
Several flights were delayed due to stoppages by Olympic
Airways employees and air traffic controllers.
</P>
<P>
Several minor electricity blackouts were caused by a 48-hour
strike of the Public power company employees which started
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In the northern Greek port city of Thessaloniki, striking
workers holding red and black banners staged a rally today in
front of the city's labour center. They also presented a
resolution calling for real wages increases in 1998 to the General
Secretary George Lyssarides of the Ministry of Macedonia-Thrace.
</P>
<P>
In the cities of Piraeus and Patras, striking workers also held
similar rallies.
</P>
<P>
Trade union official described today's strike as "a success"
with a 70 percent rate of participation in public utilities and as
much as 80 percent in parts of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in Athens today, GSEE President Christos
Polyzogopoulos said that the large participation in the strike
sent a warning that contemplated restrictions in social insurance
rights would not pass, and measures were needed against
unemployment, with the establishment of a 35-hour week at the
forefront.
</P>
<P>
After the rally, striking workers marched to the Greek
Parliament and handed a petition to Parliament President Apostolos
Kaklamanis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
