<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAOLANGDI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Experts say the Xiaolangdi
Dam and reservoir will efficiently mitigate water shortages in the Yellow
River Valleys.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages along the river, China's second longest, are
caused by arid climate, diversion of water for industrial and
agricultural purposes and a lack of major water conservation
projects in the lower reaches of the river.
</P>
<P>
Xiaolangdi Dam, being built in the middle reaches of the Yellow
River, is the second largest in China only after the Three Gorges
Dam under construction on the Yanytze.
</P>
<P>
Once in operation, the Xiaolangdi reservoir will supply 4
billion cubic meters more of water than the river does at present
to its lower reaches in spring and summer, when water supply is in
shortage.
</P>
<P>
The multipurpose project has a storage capacity of 12.6 billion
cubic meters, a level substantially higher than that of most of
China's reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
The amount of water used in the upper and middle reaches of the
Yellow River is increasing but the annual growth rate in water
consumption is dropping, experts say. Therefore, they add,
Xiaolangdi should provide ample water for irrigation, drinking and
power generation for many years.
</P>
<P>
Water shortages along the Yellow River lasted for 150 days last
year and 190 days this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say careful use of water by residents and industrial
enterprises can mitigate the seriousness of water shortages.
</P>
</TEXT>
