<HEADLINE> EPA Agrees to Bury Nuke Waste in New Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles, October 23 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Environment Protection
Agency(EPA) today preliminarily agreed with a plan to bury nuclear
waste in Southeastern New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The decision sets the stage for the so-called Waste Isolation
Pilot Plant, completed in 1988 at a cost of 1.8 billion U.S.
dollars, to open after two decades of heated debate.
</P>
<P>
The EPA said the final ruling will be made public next Spring
and the public has four months to comment on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Environmentalists have raised questions over many years about
the safety of the repository, such as curently drilling in the
area and hauling radioactive waste hundedss of miles to the
repository.
</P>
<P>
According to reports coming from New Mexico, the EPA promised
the respository would prevent human radiation doses higher than
the equivalenty of about 2 chest X-rays per year, and markers
would be placed around the site to discourage future generations
from mining or drilling in the area.
</P>
<P>
The repository would receive about 37,700 waste shipments over
the next 35 years. The waste shipments would largely come from
defense industry in 10 states, including California, Colorado,
Idahoalenty, Illinois, Nevada and Ohio.
</P>
<P>
The project is considered a part of a strategy for cleaning up
government nuclear wast sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
