<HEADLINE> China to Buy U.S. Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite good harvests in
recent years in China, this country is prepared to buy wheat from
the United States, as a way of reducing trade deficit on the U.S.
side, a high ranking Chinese official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Economic and Trade Delegation is going to make
an order for the commodity with an amount of 700,000 tons,
delegation head and Vice Chairman of the State Planning Commission
Zeng Peiyan said in an interview with Xinhua and local media.
</P>
<P>
"The move shows that China has been taking active measures to
solve the trade deficit problem and we want the U.S. side to
understand this practical attitude on the Chinese part," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said during the visit the delegation will make broad
contacts with the U.S. business community and try to lay foundation
for further cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The contracts worth as much as four billion U.S. dollars that
will be signed during the visit include also the purchase by China
of Boeing airplanes worth between two to three billion dollars, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there are also other contracts expected to be signed
after the delegation comes back to China, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhenyu, deputy head of the delegation and Vice Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation who joined Zeng in the
interview, said China is taking measures beneficial to foreign
exporters.
</P>
<P>
From October 1, China reduced tariffs from an average of 23
percent to 17 percent and by 2000 it will further reduce to the
average level of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Both China and the U.S. should make efforts to address trade
deficit, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. enterprises should be more competitive against Europeans
and Japanese in terms of commodity prices and technologies and the
U.S. government should provide financial support including loans
on favorable terms to exporters and loosen restrictions on
high-tech exports, he continued.
</P>
<P>
Both Zeng and Sun expressed their conviction that the
forthcoming state visit by President Jiang Zemin to the U.S. will
produce positive results in promoting Sino-U.S. economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The discussions between him and President Bill Clinton late
this month are expected to cover bilateral cooperation in the
fields of energy (including nuclear energy), environment
protection and aerospace, said Zeng. He expressed hope that both
sides will reach agreements to create better conditions for the
cooperation between businesses of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived in New York on Tuesday after touring
Los Angles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
