<HEADLINE> CPAFFC Bridges Sino-US Friendship (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Sister city relationships have
flourished since China and the United States established
diplomatic ties in 1979, Qi Huaiyuan, president of the Chinese
People's Association for Friendship with Foreign Countries
(CPAFFC), said this in a recent interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
With the help of the CPAFFC, 28 pairs of provinces and states
and 89 pairs of cities of the two countries have established
sister city relationships, covering nearly every Chinese province
and medium-to-large city, he said.
</P>
<P>
Examples include ties between Beijing and Washington, D.C.,
Shanghai and San Francisco, and Guangzhou and Los Angeles, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
The friendly relations among provinces, states and cities have
opened an important channel for semi-official and non-governmental
exchanges between the U.S. and China, Qi said, adding that the
sister city relationships have had a positive impact on the growth
of Sino-U.S. ties.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of CPAFFC's efforts is to increase mutual
understanding and friendship between China and the U.S., Qi
said. Because of this, he added, CPAFFC receives many visitors
from all walks of life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Since last year, CPAFFC's guests from the United States have
included Brent Scowcroft, former U.S Assistant to the President
for National Security Affairs; Kentucky Gov. Paul Patton;
California Gov. Pete Wilson; San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown; and
Gary Locke, the first Chinese-American governor of Washington
state, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
These U.S. guests met with Chinese President Jiang Zemin during
their stays in China, Qi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Tumbles in Global Selloff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average tumbled almost 200 points Thursday as a big selloff in
Hong Kong influenced other major markets, triggering a global
stock slide.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, an index of 30 multinational companies whose profits
have already been pinched by the mounting economic turmoil in
Southeast Asia, fell 186.88 to 7,847.77.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also sank by about 2 percent, slightly
less than the 2.3 percent loss suffered by the Dow, which still
boasts a 21.7 percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's main stock index plunged 10 percent Thursday,
took an even heavier toll on other overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei stock average fell 3.0 percent in Japan, which
exports heavily to Southeast Asia. The FT-SE 100 fell 3.1 percent
in Britain. And in Germany, the DAX index fell 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
But once the investors pulled all that money out of stocks,
they put it onto the U.S. Treasury bonds. The sudden worldwide
demand sent bond prices soaring, and yields declined to 6.34
percent.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index has tumbled 25 percent this
week, which has deepened fears about weakening profits for
companies that depend on Asian markets for some of their profits.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange and by more than a 3-to-1 margin on the Nasdaq
Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 669.32 million shares as against the third
largest tally ever, and Nasdaq volume totaled 818.87 million
shares, the seventh busiest day ever.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 17.80 to 950.69, the
NYSE composite index fell 9.31 to 499.49, and the Nasdaq composite
index fell 36.83 to 1,671.25.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.89 to 449.36,
and the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange composite
index fell 10.35 to 703.39.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CPAFFC Bridges Sino-US Friendship (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CPAFFC also has organized Chinese groups from such sectors as
economy and trade, urban development, environmental protection and
culture to visit the United States, the CPAFFC president said.
</P>
<P>
Qi, a veteran diplomat, told Xinhua that in recent years
exchanges between the two countries have reached a much greater
dimension than ever before. He said these exchanges are
encouraging for improved bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
As two of the biggest and most influential countries in the
world, China and the U.S. should establish a new cooperative
relationship oriented to the 21st century. This new relationship
should be based on mutual understanding and trust, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, many people in the political community and
non-government sectors of the U.S. either misunderstand or have a
biased view of China, Qi said, adding that CPAFFC still has much
to do to change these perceptions.
</P>
<P>
So that more people in the U.S. can learn more about China,
CPAFFC has encouraged exchanges between the young people of both
countries. Last year, jazz bands from Yale University and a
U.S. middle school performed in Beijing and Shanghai. Members of
the jazz bands also met with Chinese students in Qinghua
University in Beijing, Qi recalled.
</P>
<P>
To mark the signing of the Shanghai communique 25 years ago,
CPAFFC invited 85 students from 22 states in the U.S. to Shanghai
for talks with their Chinese counterparts, Qi said.
</P>
<P>
Qi said he believes that exchanges between the young people of
the two countries has laid a foundation for developing long-term
friendly relations.
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC has also established links with non-governmental
organizations in the educational, cultural, business and religious
sectors in the U.S. These organizations include the U.S.-China
People's Friendship Association, Harvard University, Yale
University, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints, the Walt
Disney Group, the U.S. Press Editors Association and Time-Warner
Communications.
</P>
<P>
On the pending state visit by President Jiang Zemin to the US,
Qi said that Jiang's state visit will surely add to the great
impetus created by CPAFFC's work with the U.S.
</P>
<P>
He told Xinhua that CPAFFC will make more friends in the
political, entrepreneurial and press communities of the U.S. to
consolidate and expand the invaluable friendship between the
people of the two countries. He hopes that these friends will do
more things beneficial to the friendship between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
"In one word, we play a role of bridge and go-between for
Sino-U.S. friendship," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
