<HEADLINE> Shennongjia, Natural Lab for Scientists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Shennongjia State Reserve in
central China's Hubei Province has become a hot spot for
scientific researchers from China and abroad who are intrigued by
its abundant geological resources and unique primeval forest.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Jinxing, who has lived in the reserve for four years, is
fascinated by the mystery of its primitive inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
Zhang has found strange hair, footprints and excrement in
Shengnongjia. He has also met red-haired wild boar and white sheep
in his travels.
</P>
<P>
After five years of research Hu Hongxing, a professor from the
school of biology at Wuhan University, identified 500 snub-nosed
monkeys in three categories in an 800-square-kilometer area of
Shennongjia jungle.
</P>
<P>
Hao Yongwei, a senior engineer from the provincial geological
and mineral bureau of Hubei, discovered precious stones in
Shennongjia. His findings have narrowed the search for the origin
of Heshibi, a famous jade in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 scholars and experts have been to Shennongjia
for research and at least 10 papers written in the past 10 years
on rare animals and plants. 
</P>
</TEXT>
