<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Tumbles in Global Selloff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Dow Jones industrial
average tumbled almost 200 points Thursday as a big selloff in
Hong Kong influenced other major markets, triggering a global
stock slide.
</P>
<P>
The Dow, an index of 30 multinational companies whose profits
have already been pinched by the mounting economic turmoil in
Southeast Asia, fell 186.88 to 7,847.77.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock measures also sank by about 2 percent, slightly
less than the 2.3 percent loss suffered by the Dow, which still
boasts a 21.7 percent gain for the year.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's main stock index plunged 10 percent Thursday,
took an even heavier toll on other overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei stock average fell 3.0 percent in Japan, which
exports heavily to Southeast Asia. The FT-SE 100 fell 3.1 percent
in Britain. And in Germany, the DAX index fell 4.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
But once the investors pulled all that money out of stocks,
they put it onto the U.S. Treasury bonds. The sudden worldwide
demand sent bond prices soaring, and yields declined to 6.34
percent.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, the Hang Seng index has tumbled 25 percent this
week, which has deepened fears about weakening profits for
companies that depend on Asian markets for some of their profits.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-1 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange and by more than a 3-to-1 margin on the Nasdaq
Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume totaled 669.32 million shares as against the third
largest tally ever, and Nasdaq volume totaled 818.87 million
shares, the seventh busiest day ever.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 17.80 to 950.69, the
NYSE composite index fell 9.31 to 499.49, and the Nasdaq composite
index fell 36.83 to 1,671.25.
</P>
<P>
The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 8.89 to 449.36,
and the small-company dominated American Stock Exchange composite
index fell 10.35 to 703.39.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Buy U.S. Wheat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Despite good harvests in
recent years in China, this country is prepared to buy wheat from
the United States, as a way of reducing trade deficit on the U.S.
side, a high ranking Chinese official announced here today.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Chinese Economic and Trade Delegation is going to make
an order for the commodity with an amount of 700,000 tons,
delegation head and Vice Chairman of the State Planning Commission
Zeng Peiyan said in an interview with Xinhua and local media.
</P>
<P>
"The move shows that China has been taking active measures to
solve the trade deficit problem and we want the U.S. side to
understand this practical attitude on the Chinese part," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said during the visit the delegation will make broad
contacts with the U.S. business community and try to lay foundation
for further cooperation between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The contracts worth as much as four billion U.S. dollars that
will be signed during the visit include also the purchase by China
of Boeing airplanes worth between two to three billion dollars, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Besides, there are also other contracts expected to be signed
after the delegation comes back to China, he added.
</P>
<P>
Sun Zhenyu, deputy head of the delegation and Vice Minister of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation who joined Zeng in the
interview, said China is taking measures beneficial to foreign
exporters.
</P>
<P>
From October 1, China reduced tariffs from an average of 23
percent to 17 percent and by 2000 it will further reduce to the
average level of developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Both China and the U.S. should make efforts to address trade
deficit, he said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. enterprises should be more competitive against Europeans
and Japanese in terms of commodity prices and technologies and the
U.S. government should provide financial support including loans
on favorable terms to exporters and loosen restrictions on
high-tech exports, he continued.
</P>
<P>
Both Zeng and Sun expressed their conviction that the
forthcoming state visit by President Jiang Zemin to the U.S. will
produce positive results in promoting Sino-U.S. economic ties.
</P>
<P>
The discussions between him and President Bill Clinton late
this month are expected to cover bilateral cooperation in the
fields of energy (including nuclear energy), environment
protection and aerospace, said Zeng. He expressed hope that both
sides will reach agreements to create better conditions for the
cooperation between businesses of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The delegation arrived in New York on Tuesday after touring
Los Angles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai GM Announces Big Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The visiting Chinese trade
delegation witnessed here today another expensive signing in which
the Shanghai GM will purchase vehicle component sets worth 200
million U.S. dollars from General Motors Corporation (GM).
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai GM is partly a baby company of GM, the largest
auto maker in the world. It is an equally divided joint venture
launched formally in June this year in the booming Pudong New Area
of Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The agreement calls for General Motors to export up to 18,000
component sets for a Buick mid-luxury car and its derivatives to
support pre-launch and start-up activities.
</P>
<P>
Singing the agreement were Hu Maoyuan, president of the
Shanghai GM, and Louis Hughes, executive vice president of General
Motors and president of GM's International Operations.
</P>
<P>
Hu said, "Approval of this agreement is an indication of the
significance of Shanghai GM. By enabling General Motors to export
a significant number of vehicle subassemblies into China, the
Chinese government is demonstrating their backing to expedite the
Shanghai GM project."
</P>
<P>
The 200 million U.S. dollars will be shared by both sides of
the investors, apart from the 1.5 billion U.S. dollars initially
agreed for building up the joint venture, according to Hu.
</P>
<P>
Hughes said that "We are pleased to provide the pre-launched
production support of Shanghai GM. The success of the Shanghai GM
is critical to our global strategies, in addition to providing an
excellent export opportunity from North America to China."
</P>
<P>
Shanghai GM was set up between the Shanghai Automotive Industry
Corporation and the General Motors. The new company is GM's 18th
venture in China. It is planned to manufacture and sell passenger
vehicles in China and for export.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that since the contract of the joint venture was signed
in Beijing in March 25, everything has been going on smoothly. He
said the two sides put up the signing ahead of schedule mainly
because the company is in urgent need of the components. The plant
is expected to roll out sample cars by the end of 1998. Official
production will start in April, 1999, according to the president
of the Shanghai GM.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials attending the signing ceremony included Zeng
Peiyan, Vice Chairman of the State Planning Commission; Sun
Zhenyu, Vice Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation;
and Lu Fuyuan, Vice Minister of the Machine Building Industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Shares Plunge on Asian Market Turmoil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Major stock markets in Europe
all extended Wednesday's losses and ended sharply lower as
shockwaves from Hong Kong's plunge rocked the markets.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index had dropped 222 points at one stage
early today before closing at 4,991.50 points, down 3.06 percent
or 157.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that Wall Street's relative stability in the face
of global stock market turmoil saved London prices from disaster.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that market movements were also exaggerated by the
new SETs trading system the London market adopted on Monday.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 28 billion pounds (45.7 billion
US dollars) were wiped off the value of UK's leading stock index
and shares of companies that do business in Asia were among the
hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
Shares prices in Frankfurt also slid, with the DAX-30 index
closing at 3,977.26, down 194.19 points or 4.66 percent, once
again below the key 4,000-point level, as the plunge in Hong Kong
hurt sentiment.
</P>
<P>
A trader said that "while there is no real reason for us to
react so strongly to what goes on in Southeast Asia, the losses
are having a psychological influence".
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index followed the whole world and ended
101.19 points lower at 2,856.87. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0195 </DOCNO>
