<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Program to Develop Inland Fishery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's Fisheries and
Aquatic Resources Development Ministry has launched a special
program to develop the inland fishery sector, a ministry official
said today.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to net in 50,000 metric tons of fish annually
by year 2000 and to stop import of canned fish.
</P>
<P>
As an initial step, the ministry plans to provide houses for
inland fishermen near tanks and reservoirs where they are already
engaged in fishing. Each house builder will be granted 25,000
Rupees (424 U.S. dollars) under the program.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, such subsidy was only available for coastal fishermen.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has strengthened management in three fish breeding
centers in inland areas. A new center will be operative on
November 1, the official said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
