<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economic Zones' Exports Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Export earnings generated by the
Philippines' economic zones reached 7.3 billion U.S. dollars for
the first eight months of this year, rising nearly 83 percent from
the year-ago level of 4 billion dollars, local press reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the export receipts came from special economic
zones, whose earnings grew by a whopping 193 percent to 4.4
billion dollars from 1.5 billion dollars of the same period last
year, said the reports, citing data from the Philippine Economic
Zone Authority (PEZA).
</P>
<P>
Among the special economic zones, the Laguna Technopark Inc.,
which houses Toshiba Information Equipment, posted the highest
revenues with 1.97 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from the regular economic zones or those
managed by the government also registered slight improvement
during the period.
</P>
<P>
As of August, the four government-controlled economic
processing zones gained export receipts of 2.9 billion dollars, up
18 percent from a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
PEZA officials were quoted as explaining that the surge in
export earnings was due to the rising number of economic zones in
the country which attracted a large number of export-oriented
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
There are 54 economic zones or industrial estates in the
country, which have been a major foreign exchange earner for the
government in recent years.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the economic zones' export earnings hit 6.5 billion
dollars, accounting for one-third of the country's total export
income that year. The PEZA expected these zones to earn 10 billion
dollars in export income for the whole of 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
