<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Rice Production to Decline This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jakarta, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's production of
unhusked rice will drop to only 49 million tons, 4 percent lower
than the 51 million tons of 1996, a cabinet minister said.
</P>
<P>
"However, this should not cause too much worry because the
national rice stock remains stable thanks to last year's harvest,
which was quite successful," Minister of Agriculture Sjarifudin
Baharsjah said in Cirebon, West Java, reports reaching here today
said.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the decline of rice production to the
prolonged dry season in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the National Logistic Agency, the national rice
stock is 3 million tons, enough for four to five months to come.
</P>
<P>
Baharsjah said that judging from past experiences, it is likely
that the coming harvest season will also be successful because
droughts are usually followed by good harvests.
</P>
<P>
He said next year's rice output may reach around 52 million
tons. He also called on farmers to use quality seeds to carry out
early planting to ensure a good harvest.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government also planned to increase rice fields
by 500,000 to 1 million hectares next year to boost production.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, formerly the biggest rice importer in the world,
became self-sufficient in rice production in 1984.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
