<HEADLINE> Indonesia Upbeat on IMF Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian government officials
remain optimistic about talks with the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) on an assistance package aimed at restoring confidence in
the country's financial markets.
</P>
<P>
"The talks continue and we are making progress. Yes, I am
optimistic," Trade and Industry Minister Tunky Ariwibowo said here
last night after meeting President Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, Indonesia would not compromise on its national
car program, under which a private company is to manufacture
sedans in collaboration with Kia Motors of South Korea, official
sources today quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Some analysts have said scrapping the program may form part of
the discussions with the IMF.
</P>
<P>
"What we are discussing is how to synchronize our program,"
Tunky said. "Our program, such as the national car and
deregulation, will continue to be developed."
</P>
<P>
At a seminar on Wednesday, Charles Harinowo, director of the
central bank's Money Market Department, said the talks are
proceeding well and are at a final stage.
</P>
<P>
Neither Tunky nor Harinowo would say when the talks would be
concluded or what size the package might be.
</P>
<P>
However, they denied a report that the IMF team had concluded
its discussions and that details of any package would be announced
after an IMF board meeting in Washington at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia said on October 8 that it was approaching the IMF,
the World Bank and the Asian Development Bank for assistance in
restoring confidence in the markets and stabilizing the rupiah
which has depreciated by about 50 percent against the U.S. dollar
since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
State Secretary Moerdiono had said earlier that the IMF team
was in the final stage of discussions with Indonesian authorities
and that the talks could be over by the weekend.
</P>
<P>
World Bank officials have said the package is expected to
include financial and technical support for Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The rupiah has stabilized against the U.S. dollar as the market
is waiting for the announcement of the much talked-about financial
package from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the rupiah closed firmer against the U.S. dollar
at 3,560/90 compared to the opening of 3,610/30 in the morning
session after it reached its lowest level of 3,680 in midday
trading when the central bank stepped in with a small amount of
dollars, dealers said today.
</P>
<P>
As the rupiah stabilized, share prices on the Jakarta Stock
Exchange declined sharply with the main price gauge plunging below
500 points on regional market losses, brokers said.
</P>
<P>
The composite index closed 2.2 percent, or 11.09 points, lower
to 494.13 Thursday with a total 658 million shares changing hands
in the regular market valued at 136.85 million dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
