<HEADLINE> India to Allow Private Sector Airline Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Indian Civil Aviation
Ministry is to announce a fresh package of measures soon to allow
private sector airline operations, ministry sources said here
today.
</P>
<P>
The package is also expected to withdraw guidelines which force
airlines to operate on uneconomic routes and end the government's
monopoly on air traffic control services.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will retain the existing restrictions on
participation of foreign airlines in the domestic sector. Foreign
investors will be allowed to invest up to 40 percent in domestic
airlines while non-resident Indians/overseas corporate bodies will
be allowed to acquire stakes of up to 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new policy will also allow domestic airlines to fly certain
international routes, though the first right of refusal will be
given to Air India/Indian Airlines.  
</P>
</TEXT>
