<HEADLINE> U.S. to Further Support Ukraine's Economic Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The United States will give more
support to Ukraine's economic reform, Russia's Interfax news
agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. representative made the remark during the third meeting
of the economic cooperation committee of the Ukrainian-U.S. Joint
Commission, which ended here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The joint commission was set up in February, 1992, when
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma visited the United States. Its
last meeting was held in May in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Sergei Tigipko, Ukrainian Deputy Prime Minister in charge of
economic affairs and chief representative for the meeting, told a
press conference after the meeting that his country has so far
received more than one billion U.S. dollars in technological aid
since 1992, which surpassed all other countries in this field.
</P>
<P>
The United States has assisted Ukraine in hundreds of projects,
with investments totaling over 1.5 billion dollars, said another
senior Ukrainian representative.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the two sides also stressed the importance
of maintaining the stability of the macro-economy in Ukraine and
the necessity of keeping the taxation reform, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to hold the next committee meeting in the
Spring of 1998 in Washington. 
</P>
</TEXT>
