<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Further Devalues Taka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi currency taka
will be further devalued against the U.S. dollar by 0.89 percent
in buying and 1.11 percent in selling, the country's central bank,
the Bangladesh Bank, said today.
</P>
<P>
The buying and selling rates of the dollar will be 44.85 and
45.15 taka respectively from Sunday, compared to the present rates
of 44.45 and 44.65 taka.
</P>
<P>
The resultant change in the middle rate will be from 44.55 to
45.00 taka per dollar, according to a release issued by the bank.
</P>
<P>
This will be the 10th devaluation of the taka since the Awami
League government took power on June 23, 1996. The taka's value
has depreciated by a total of 8.61 percent in the last 14 months.
</P>
<P>
In earlier devaluations, the adjustment range in the buying and
selling rates was similar. But this time, the gap between the
buying and selling rates is widened from 0.2 to 0.3 taka per
dollar. This was done to encourage dealers to access the interbank
market rather than the central bank for their funds procurement
and disposal, the release added.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation will benefit the central bank and other
authorized dealers (banks) as they will buy dollars at lower
prices and sell it at higher prices, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Exporters will be affected as they will have to buy dollars at
a higher rate by paying 0.1 taka more for each dollar while
receiving 0.1 taka less for each dollar in their export bills.
</P>
<P>
The latest downward adjustment will also sensitize the foreign
exchange market. The price of the dollar, which is now traded at
more than 46 taka in the market, will increase further, observers
here said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Conference on Barrage May Be Held in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A proposed international
conference on the necessity of a Ganges barrage is likely to be
held here in February next year.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the donor community, governments of the
countries in the Ganges basin, research organizations and local
and foreign experts will be invited to the conference, The
Financial Express today quoted Bangladeshi Minister of Water
Resources Abdur Razzak as saying.
</P>
<P>
The prime objectives of the conference is to give donors and
the international community a clear idea of the necessity of the
Ganges barrage to protect almost one-third of Bangladesh from
environmental hazards, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Issues of protecting mangrove forest, wildlife and fish
population from destruction and expanding irrigation facility to
augment food production by increasing sweet water flows in Ganges
tributaries in Bangladesh would be discussed at the conference, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The conference would enable the donors to find out ways for
supporting the mega project essential for the survival of at least
40 million people in Bangladesh, the minister stated.
</P>
<P>
Countries in the region -- India, Nepal, Bhutan and Bangladesh
-- would also be able to forge a concrete view leading to regional
cooperation for the implementation of the project, the minister
said.
</P>
<P>
India already intends to extend technical assistance to
Bangladesh's efforts toward the construction of the Ganges
barrage, the minister said, adding that the Netherlands, Britain,
Italy and South Korea have also shown interest in the project.
</P>
<P>
A technical commission of the Asian Development Bank is already
in Bangladesh to prepare a feasibility report on the project and
the attitude of the World Bank toward the project is also
positive, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Japan has already expressed its readiness to support
Bangladesh in organizing the proposed international conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
