<HEADLINE> Romania, Bulgaria, Greece Promote Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Romania, Bulgaria and Greece
today agreed to make joint efforts to promote trilateral
cooperation and stability in Europe.
</P>
<P>
A joint communique, issued after the meeting of foreign
ministers of the three countries in the Romanian city of Sinaia,
agreed that Romania and Bulgaria should support each other in
their efforts to enter the European Union (EU) and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Greece will "do its utmost to back" Romania and Bulgaria to
achieve their strategic aims, the communique added.
</P>
<P>
Romania and Bulgaria also reiterated the principles of
non-interference in each other internal affairs, non-aggression
and maintaining good-neighborly ties.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers also discussed cooperation in development
of transport and infrastructure and the fight against organized
crime.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference after their meeting, the three said their
countries would soon coordinate their stands with Turkey in a bid
to maintain peace and stability in southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Romanian Foreign Minister Adrian Severin also proposed setting
up a United Nations-sponsored center to cope with possible crises
in southeastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Greek Foreign Minister Theodoros Pangalos proposed holding a
summit of the three countries and inviting Turkey to attend.
</P>
<P>
The annual contact between Romania, Bulgaria and Greece was
initiated by Greece which hosted the first trilateral
foreign-minister-level meeting in August 1995.
</P>
<P>
The second meeting was held in Bulgaria in March 1996. The
three foreign ministers decided today that the fourth meeting and
a summit of the three countries would be held in Athens next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
