Lufthansa Services Enterprises Ltd. is planning to set up a 3
million U.S. dollar factory in Myanmar's capital Yangon to begin
aircraft catering services for international airlines.
</P>
<P>
According to a memorandum of understanding signed here Thursday
between the Hong Kong firm and the Myanmar Ministry of Transport,
the factory will be built near Yangon International Airport within
one year under a build, operate and transfer system, the official
newspaper The New Light of Myanmar reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong firm will operate the factory, which will produce
2,500 packets of food daily, for 10 years in Myanmar before
transferring it to the Myanmar side, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
There are now 18 international airlines operating regular and
chartered flights to Yangon International Airport, which is
handling more and more passengers and freights due to the
development of Myanmar's economy and tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, tourist arrivals in Myanmar
reached 128,714 in the first six months of this year, increasing
10.7 percent over the previous year. Of the in-coming tourists,
51,845 came by air.
</P>
<P>
The statistics also show that tourists visiting Myanmar in the
1996-97 fiscal year ending in March were 248,225, of whom 110,038
arrived by air.  
</P>
