<HEADLINE> Tourists Visit Sri Lanka Despite Bomb Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Tourists continue to visit Sri
Lanka despite the October 15 bomb blast in Colombo which caused
great casualties and seriously damaged the downtown business
center, a senior official of the Ceylon Tourist Board said today.
</P>
<P>
During the first week after the blast, more than 7,000 tourists
arrived in Sri Lanka, statistics from the board said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that on October 16, the day after the
bombing, there were 1,150 tourist arrivals. However, Tourism
Minister Dharmasiri Senanayake said at a presidential news
conference last week that only 494 tourists arrived in the Sri
Lankan capital that day.
</P>
<P>
There were 288,000 arrivals from January 1 to October 21,
representing a 20-percent increase over the same period last year,
the official said.
</P>
<P>
Total arrivals in 1996 suffered a 25-percent decline from
403,000 in 1995 to 302,265.
</P>
<P>
Tour operators said almost all charter flight operators had
confirmed that they will fly to Colombo as scheduled during the
forthcoming winter season beginning November.
</P>
<P>
The Association of Group Tour Agents said that so far only
around 200 tourists had canceled their trip to this country due to
the blast.
</P>
<P>
A total of 18 people, including five Tamil rebels shot dead by
the security forces, were killed and more than 100 injured in the
bombing incident.
</P>
<P>
The powerful explosion also seriously damaged the business
compound of Colombo, making a mess of two luxury tourist hotels,
the Hilton and the Galadari.  
</P>
</TEXT>
