<HEADLINE> Bosnian Serb, French Military Leaders Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Chief of the General Staff
of Bosnian Serb Forces, Pero Colic, today reiterated his army's
determination to abide by the Bosnian peace agreement (the Dayton
Peace Agreement).
</P>
<P>
Meeting with Zak Filip Duen, visiting chief of staff of the
French armed forces, in Pale, the capital of the Bosnian Serb
Republic (Srpska), Colic said the Bosnian Serb Forces will
contribute to regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The Dayton Peace Agreement, signed in December 1995 by
representatives from the three warring factions in Bosnia-
Herzegovina and international mediators, led to an end of the 3.5
years of war in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, Colic said the international community has been
pursuing a discriminatory policy towards Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
He is hopeful that the international community will treat the
different parties in Bosnia equally and without discrimination in
the future.
</P>
<P>
Duen said during the talks that the key way out of the current
crisis in the Republic of Srpska is to hold simultaneously the
presidential and parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
Biljana Plavsic, who was elected president of the Republic of
Srpska in September 1996, is not getting along well with the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Plavsic declared on July 3 that the national assembly was
dissolved, but the Charter Court ruled on August 15 that Plavsic's
decision was invalid.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the political crisis has escalated. Plavsic called
for early parliamentary elections, which were supported by
Western countries including the United States, but the General
Staff of the Bosnian Serb Forces disagreed.
</P>
<P>
In September, President of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
Slobodan Milosevic visited the Republic of Srpska for mediation
and proposed to hold simultaneously the presidential and
parliamentary elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
