<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Bund Mirrors Double-Faced Images to World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Strolling along the Shanghai
Bund of Huangpu River, every conscious man will slow down his pace
unconsciously at the striking images mirrored in the ripples of
its tireless waves.
</P>
<P>
Decades ago, the Shanghai Bund was awashed by the monotonous
waves but the tides finally turn into a harmonious chorus as the
Chinese people strike forward in quick paces with their strong
heartbeats.
</P>
<P>
Along the west side of the river, the chimes of the former
British Customs are in silence, while the neon lights of the
Oriental Pearl TV Tower flash out the shines in the east bank
throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
After decades of humiliation for the Chinese people, the
Shanghai Bund embraces the waves as a generous host to welcome all
the investors at home and abroad since 1990.
</P>
<P>
Once known as Paris of the East, Shanghai fell asleep into its
hibernation as flocks of foreign powers stamped their feet upon
the land, tagged as a fairyland for the Western venturers.
</P>
<P>
After the 1840 Opium War, the Britons circled out their first
international settlements in 1848 and the Bund became stink under
the footsteps of the American, the French, the German, the Czech
and the Japanese later, to cite a few.
</P>
<P>
The tides flow eastwards in their own rhythm, but Shanghai is
awakened eventually with the prosperity of Pudong at the east bank
of the Huangpu river.
</P>
<P>
Against the buildings with colonial colors in the west side,
modern skyscrapers surge upwards in queues in the east bank, with
the Oriental Pearl TV Tower as the symbol for Shanghai in new
breath.
</P>
<P>
The Western conquerers prohibited the Chinese from entering
their settlements along the Bund, while the Chinese people are
extending their arms to warmly welcome all the friends around the
world.
</P>
<P>
The boom in the 1930s was a hypocrisy, studded with evils and
disasters as the local poor were frozen to death along the streets
while the foreign rich threw their coats to warm their engines.
</P>
<P>
Nowsdays, investors from over 60 countries and regions have
since put their capitals of 23.07 billion U.S. dollars upon the land
of 350 square kilometers, which attracts 72 of the top 500
companies in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Oriental Pearl TV Power, the highest in Asia, received over
600,000 visitors in its first six months, and a 94-story 460-meter
skyscraper was already under construction on August 29 as the
Shanghai World Financial Center is on its way to become the
world's tallest building.
</P>
<P>
To erase the colonial stink, China embraced Hong Kong to its
arms on July 1, 1997, restoring the national pride for 1.2 billion
people.
</P>
<P>
Now, two cable-hanging bridges fly across the Huangpu river to
link the west and the east as Shanghai is pacing ahead from an
ancient fishing outpost to a modern metropolitan with greatest
success. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Establish Insurance System for Rural Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- China is working on improving
its social insurance system for old people in the countryside in
response to its aging rural population, today's China Daily
reported.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Ministry of Civil Affairs said an improved
social old-age insurance security system will be established in
the country's rural areas by the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
By 2000, China's citizens aged 60 or older will account for
10.71 percent of the country's total population. And nearly all
Chinese farmers have to work their farmlands till they loss their
ability to do physical labor.
</P>
<P>
China started experimenting with a rural social old-age
insurance system in 1991, first in Yantai city of Shangdong
Province. It has expanded to cover more than 2,000 counties in 30
provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities.
</P>
<P>
The ministry officials said more than 82 million Chinese
farmers have so far joined the rural social old-age insurance
program, which offers a total of 12 billion yuan (about 1.45
billion US dollars) in insurance funds. China has rural population
of at least 900 million.
</P>
<P>
Under the current practice, farmers buy old-age insurance when
they are 20 years old. They pay annual premiums till they are 60
years old.
</P>
<P>
When they reach 60, the farmers will get a monthly insurance
payment of 100 yuan (about 12 US dollars) to 600 yuan (about 72 US
dollars) to support them in their remaining years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
