<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news stories from Latin America over the past few days:
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian grain output will reach 78.8
million tons in the 1997-98 season, a 1.9 percent increase over
the 1996-97 cycle.
</P>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO -- The Brazilian gross domestic product will
increase four percent this year, compared with last year.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- Panama's International Banking Center assets
reached about 34 billion U.S. dollars during the first half of
this year, 655 million dollars more than the amount at the end
1996, the National Banking Commission said.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Argentina sold 10,000 tons of chickens to
Russia this year, the biggest sale of its kind in the trade of the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- Central American countries' coffee production will
drop by 500,000 quintales during the present harvest, due to the
El Nino climate phenomenon in this region.
</P>
<P>
However, the Coffee Producing Countries Association decided to
maintain the same exporting quotas as last year.
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Sales of new cars reached 17,471 units in
September, a 32 percent increase over the same month of 1996,
</P>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA -- Colombia plans to build its first
distribution center in the customs tax free zone in this capital,
with the aim of increasing profits in the flowers business,
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian exports to the Southern Common Market
(Mercosur) will reach 20 billion dollars this year, against 18
billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Brazilian exports to Mercosur are estimated to amount to 32
billion dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- Foreign investments in Venezuela reached 2.3 billion
dollars in June, 23 percent more than the same month of
1996. 
</P>
