<HEADLINE> Italy Trade Surplus - 20 B in First 8 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Italy's foreign trade continues to
improve with an estimated surplus of 36 trillion lire (about 20
billion U.S. dollars) in the first eight months of this year, the
Italian Foreign Exchange said here today.
</P>
<P>
The latest surplus resulted from exports worth 253 trillion
lire (14.2 billion U.S. dollars) and imports worth 217 trillion
(12.7 billion dollars), covering all operations, including
transactions less than 20 million lire, the office declared.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed a large increase in the surplus with the
U.S., which was up from six to eight billion dollars in the first
eight months.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, engineering and textile products are
still the strongest engine driving Italy's export success. Since
the country is lacking in energy resources, energy imports created
the largest deficits, costing more than 19 trillion lire (11
billion dollars). 
</P>
