<HEADLINE> Concerns Raised in U.S. about Pepper Spray </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Pepper spray could be a
lethal weapon in the hands of civilians without training, the San
Francisco district attorney's office said today.
</P>
<P>
Investigators in the office have been banned to use the spray
because of its implication in in-custody death.
</P>
<P>
The latest victim was a 39-year-old accountant, who died after
being sprayed by local police in San Francisco. The man suffered
from asthma, a medical condition that experts believe could have
triggered a lethal reaction to pepper.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that pepper spray could be lethal to people under
certain illnesses including asthma, heart problems and
schizophrenia. It can also cause lethal reactions in those under
the influence of drugs and alcohol. 
</P>
</TEXT>
