<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interest Rate Cut Benefits State Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists and
enterpreneurs hailed yesterday's interest rate cut as an important
measure to reduce the debt burden on State-owned enterprises,
reported today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
China yesterday reduced the interest rates on deposits and
loans by an average of 1.1 and 1.5 percentage points respectively
after lowering the rates twice last year.
</P>
<P>
As more than 80 percent of the State banks' six trillion yuan
(722.89 billion US dollars) of loans flow to State-owned
enterprises, said an official with the Bank of China, the latest
rate cut means that the interest charges to these companies can be
reduced by 50 billion yuan (six billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to Huang Jinhe, vice-president of the State-owned
China First Automobile Group Co., his companies technical
renovation fund, capital investment and working capital fund
mainly rely on bank loans.
</P>
<P>
He said, the interest rate cut will save the company more than
100 million yuan (12 million US dollars) in interest, from the
total 120 million US dollars in interest annually.
</P>
<P>
Qiu Zhongwei, an official with China Huaneng Group, said 75
percent of the investment for his company's power plants come from
bank loans. The rate cut means the company can save 27 million
dollars in interest costs annually.
</P>
<P>
Dong Chen, a researcher with China Securities Co. Ltd, said the
rate cut will help build staying power for the country's sustained
economic growth by stimulating consumption and investment.
</P>
<P>
The rate cut would also result in a strong push for the
securities market, which will create a sound environment for
State-owned firms' transformation into joint stock companies, said
the economists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0239 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Mission To Assess DPRK Food Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 23 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations delegation left
here today for the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) to
assess this year's harvest and evaluate food aid needed in that
country.
</P>
<P>
The mission, mounted jointly by the UN Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) and the World Food program (WFP), is the latest
in a series to go to the DPRK since its agriculture was devastated
by floods in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The mission will estimate this year's harvest and evaluate the
country's food import requirements including food aid for the
coming year.
</P>
<P>
This year, serious drought hit the country in the crucial
growing months from June to August, and Typhoon Winnie breached
sea defenses and caused damaging floods later.
</P>
<P>
The last joint FAO/WFP Crop and Food Supply Assessment Mission,
which visited the DPRK in August, advocated urgent international
assistance in the form of food, agricultural rehabilitation and
vital inputs of seed and fertilizers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
