<HEADLINE> Beijing Lefts Price Controls on Chinese Cabbage  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Beijing has 40,000 hectares of land under vegetables, half of
which was developed after 1994, and it is increasing that amount
by 1,300 hectares annually. Better production and a large influx
of food from other parts of the country allow Beijing residents to
buy fresh vegetables like cucumbers, tomatoes, and celery
everywhere, even in winter.
</P>
<P>
As late as in the early 1990s, the selection was still limited to
cabbage, potatoes and carrots. The cabbage used to play a major role
in controling vegetable prices, because it was cheap and
plentiful, Tao noted.
</P>
<P>
State-owned vegetable market in Beijing sold some 100 million
kg of cabbage at 0.26 yuan (about 0.03 US dollars) a kg last
year. That was only one tenth of the price of tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
This year's cabbage price has not yet been revealed. However,
some residents said that a rise in price is inevitable. They said
"We'll treat it normally."
</P>
<P>
The municipal government will provide a subsidy of ten yuan to
residents who live below the poverty line to soften the blow of
the new policy on poor families.
</P>
<P>
"About 20,000 residents will receive the money before the end
of this month," said Ding Changli, a Municipal Bureau of Civil
Affairs official.  
</P>
</TEXT>
