<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Red Tide Leaves 89 Tons of Dead Fish in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The red tide affecting the
Gulf coasts of Tamaulipas state have caused the death of some 89
tons of fish, Carlos Castro, Health secretary of the state said
today.
</P>
<P>
The official explained the most affected zones by the red tide
measuring some 420 kilometers (262 miles), from Matamoros to the
Almada village, in Tamaulipas.
</P>
<P>
Castro said the phenomenon has caused the death of dozens of
marine birds, such as seagulls and pelicans, and to prevent that
sanitary fills were created in the region.
</P>
<P>
Environment, Natural Resources, and Fishing Ministry sources
said that a state of alert continues taking effect in the zone and
a temporary ban on the capture of scale species was decreed.
</P>
<P>
The red tide appeared for the first time the first days of this
month in some areas of the Gulf of Mexico and disappeared a little
afterwards, but reappeared October 14 with more strength.
</P>
<P>
The red tide appears at the time of algae reproduction, that
thrive in the region diminishing the oxygen content of the water,
which in turn kills many marine species, mainly fish and birds
that feed on them.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted the decree of temporary interdictions,
because if some fish affected by the phenomenon are consumed by
humans, it can cause them intoxications.
</P>
<P>
The presence of the red tide in Tamaulipas coastal waters was
termed alarming, so the Navy Ministry and the Mexican Navy are
patrolling to prevent the capture of fish during the
interdiction. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
