<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Central Bank Sees Lower Lending Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines has expressed confidence that banks' prime lending
rates would progressively go down to below 20 percent by the end
of the year, the local newspaper Manila Standard said today.
</P>
<P>
Central bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as saying
Thursday that banks' lending rates are expected to drop as banks'
liquidity situation returns to normal with a two-percentage-point
reduction in liquidity reserves.
</P>
<P>
At the height of the currency crisis last month, the central
bank boosted banks' liquidity reserves requirement to a record
high of 8 percent in a bid to siphon off excess money from the
financial system.
</P>
<P>
But the move catapulted banks' lending rates, particularly
inter-bank call loan rates which once jumped to as high as 170
percent last month.
</P>
<P>
The central bank earlier decided to reduce the liquidity
reserves requirement to 6 percent, one percentage point down on
October 15 and another point on November 15.
</P>
<P>
Singson said banks would liquefy the special series government
securities they had earlier purchased from the central bank to
meet the hiked liquidity reserves requirement.
</P>
<P>
This is expected to immediately ease the pressure on the
inter-bank market and, consequently, lending rates, he explained.
</P>
<P>
He also assured the public that the country's banking system
remains in a relatively good shape given the present abnormal
market conditions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
