<HEADLINE> State- and Non-State-Run Schools to Have Same Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Students of non-government-run
schools have finally had their student cards declared legal
documents, allowing them to enjoy various ticket discounts,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Teachers and students in non-government-run schools should
enjoy the same rights as their counterparts in State-run schools,
according to the Regulations for Non-government-run Schools which
took effect on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Students and teachers of these non-government-run schools have
even more reason to be happy: greater government support and
improved management supervision promises healthy development of
their schools.
</P>
<P>
The regulations will standardize this practice of equality and
push it forward, said Huang Rao, director of the Department for
Adult Education under the State Education Commission (SEC).
</P>
<P>
The regulations say that non-government-run schools are part of
the overall educational system.
</P>
<P>
The attractiveness of non-government-run schools will be
heightened for potential student and teacher applicants, said Liu
Xiaodong, an official from the National Association of Vocational
Education of China.
</P>
<P>
Delegates called for the establishment of a committee to bridge
the information gap between executive departments and school
operators. Statistics last year indicated that China had more than
50,000 non-government-run educational institutions, staffed by
400,000 teachers and serving 9.8 million students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
