<HEADLINE> Iraq Urged to Comply With UN Security Council Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations today adopted a resolution demanding Iraq to
cooperate fully with the UN Special Commission in accordance with
relevant resolutions, which constitute the governing standard of
Iraq compliance.
</P>
<P>
The resolution was adopted with 10 votes for and 5 votes of
abstention, which are Russia, France, China, Egypt and Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The Council has demanded in particular that Iraq without delay
allow the Special Commission inspection teams immediate,
unconditional and unrestricted access to any and all areas,
facilities, equipment, records and means of transportation.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Iraq's foreign minister Mohammed Said
Al-Sahaf on Thursday denounced the UN decision to consider
additional sanctions against Baghdad at any time.
</P>
<P>
Al-Sahaf said the vote reflected a decision by Britain and the
United States "to impose their own sick motives and norms on the
Security Council."
</P>
<P>
"It is to our leadership and to the Iraqi people to decide what
are the alternatives, in order to protect our country against this
flagrant preparation to impose more injustices on our country and
our people," said the foreign minister. 
</P>
