<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unravelling Mystery Of Old Tibetan Court Music </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A recent performance of
300-year-old court music in Tibet presented music that had to be
deciphered by a Tibetan musician.
</P>
<P>
Guengdui Pagya, a 44-year-old assistant professor at Tibet
University, began to work on a collection of court music five
years ago that was the only Tibetan court music in existence. He
has done a fifth of the pieces in the collection, which date back
to the period of the fifth Dalai Lama, more than 300 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Scholars explain that traditional Tibetan music includes folk
music, Buddhist music, and court music. During the life of the
fifth Dalai Lama court music reached its highest point. In 1688,
the local governments brought a group of folk artists to Lhasa to
collect court music.
</P>
<P>
The music scores were in Tibetan and some have been
lost. Others were handed down orally, and have greatly changed in
style and content in the 300-year period.
</P>
<P>
So, what does the original court music sound like? This
question has puzzled musicians for years.
</P>
<P>
The music tells maily of history and religion. There are also
some drinking songs. Scholars say that these versions that have
the same title as oral versions, are simpler, more lively, and
unsophisticated, and some have a Nepali flavor or an Islamic
influence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Army Attracts More College Graduates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- Forty-three percent of China's
low-ranking army officers have college diplomas, nearly 54 times
the number of 1979.
</P>
<P>
In the early years of China's reform, more than 71 percent of
the junior officers of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) had only
a secondary school education, according to statistics released
today.
</P>
<P>
The Central Military Commission ordered in 1980 that junior
officers should receive higher education in military academies.
</P>
<P>
In the past 17 years, 260,000 low-ranking officers graduated
from cadet training.
</P>
<P>
Correspondence and self-study programs also boosted the
education level for officers. Of the 260,000 officers who
graduated, 20 percent took correspondence courses to gain college
diplomas.
</P>
<P>
The central military authorities have ordered that
cadet-trained officers would comprise 70 percent of the whole
force by 2000.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Zemin, Chairman of the Central Military Commission, said
the PLA should train a great number of junior and senior officers
in technology, tactics and strategy.
</P>
<P>
Civilian college graduates have also been encouraged to join
the PLA if trained in military academies.
</P>
<P>
Chinese army officers historically were from rural and poor
families, especially before 1949. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Why It Is Difficult to Buy Clothes for Kids in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 24 (Xinhua) -- While women always enjoy
shopping, Chinese mothers in large cities less do so when hunting
clothes for their children.
</P>
<P>
It is not rare they have to look into one department store after
another, but still fail to have the right choice for their "little
emperors."
</P>
<P>
It is certainly not the matter of shortage since colorful
children's wears are packed on stores' shelves as well as the
show-windows.
</P>
<P>
In analyzing the worry, an article in "China Business Daily,"
organ of the Ministry of Internal Trade, pointed out that one
problem lies in the style of the children's wear.
</P>
<P>
"Too many children's clothes are too fashion-conscious and too
redundant in designs," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Another shortfall is the lack of specifications. "Children are
growing faster and fatter, but the market does not respond to this
change quickly enough," experts concluded.
</P>
<P>
The high pricing is also a reason to shun away buyers. In a
department store, one can easily find high-priced foreign
brand-names make a bulk of the children's wear market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
