<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Cave Dweller Becomes Entrepreneur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, October 24 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese farmer left the cave he
lived in, in China's Shandong province and, through a long process
became a successful businessman and is now taking courses in
business management at Beijing University.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jiakun's story starts in 1984. That was when the then
27-year-od farmer in Jiujianpeng village left the isolation of
Longshan Mountain where he was born and had grown up. A year
later, he returned to his village, with his eyes open wider and
with more ambition and a determination to help other villagers
improve their lives.
</P>
<P>
He began with a road improvement program to help the isoated
people get in contact with the outside world he had seen. Three
years of hard labor resulted in a better road, a stone products
factory, and a farm for breeding animals. People's lives improved
considerably, and by 1990, Liu had become a role model and his
village became known for its successful struggle against adverse
conditions.
</P>
<P>
But the real challenge came in 1991 when Chinese farmers were
given greater freedom to participate in market competition, and
Liu began to see that there would be no market if they stayed in
the mountains.
</P>
<P>
So, he set his sights on urban areas. With county government's
approval, the village set up a granite processing plant in the
county seat, and two quarries. It also opened a machinery parts
factory together with one of China's major industrial enterprises.
</P>
<P>
By 1996, Jiujianpeng Industries Co., with Liu as general
manager, had more than 1.4 million yuan in profits. The poorly
dressed cave dweller now wears a neat Western suit. "It's the
reform policy that has offered us opportunities to improve our
lot," he said.
</P>
<P>
Now about half of the villagers have moved down to the county
proper and work in village-run businesses, while the others
work on acreage that all can use. Most by now live in
multi-story buildings. Some even have motor cycles or cars.
</P>
<P>
And the mobile phone, address book, and economics books in
Liu's handbag aren't there just for the fun of it but for
practical use. "Our business is expanding rapidly, we're making
more friends, and we have a lot to learn," he said.
</P>
<P>
While he is away studying, his assistants look after the
business. "Ours are township enterprises, but are developing
fast. We must try to follow advanced production and management
technology," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of AIDS Patients to Triple in Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, October 23 (Xinhua) -- The number of Ukrainians infected
with the HIV virus is expected to triple by the end of 1998 and
continue to increase for decades, officials from the National AIDS
Prevention Committee said today.
</P>
<P>
"The AIDS epidemic will continue to spread rapidly for another
20 years or so," said head of the committee Valery Ivasyuk at a
press conference.
</P>
<P>
He said even if the government steps up its AIDS awareness and
prevention campaigns, an improvement in results might not be seen
for many year considering Ukraine's living standards.
</P>
<P>
In Switzerland, the AIDS rate has started to go down after 15
years' of active campaigning.
</P>
<P>
The number of AIDS patients is increasing by 1,500 per month in
Ukraine. Most of the victims are young drug addicts between the
ages of 15-29. At the beginning of 1995, the number of registered
AIDS patients in the country reached 25,000.
</P>
<P>
Lev Khodakevytch, advisor to a U.N. AIDS program in Ukraine,
Belarus and Moldova, suggested the Ukraine focus on educating its
population in order to guard against infection rather than merely
monitor those who have already contracted the disease.
</P>
<P>
When AIDS began to spread among intravenous drug users in 1995
in southern Ukrainian cities, the government initiated a program
to combat it by equipping blood donor centers with modern AIDS
testing systems, training doctors and educating high-risk groups.
</P>
<P>
However, the program languished due to a lack of funds. In the
first eight months of 1997, the National AIDS Prevention Committee
received only 42 percent of the total needed funds, and received
60 percent and 18 percent of the needed funds in 1995 and 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0263 </DOCNO>
