<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Dollar Sinks to Three-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, October 24 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand dollar has
been on a drastic decline in trading with the American dollar in
the past two days, sinking to a three-year low at yesterday's
close.
</P>
<P>
The Kiwi closed at 0.6253 U.S. dollars Wednesday, after
plunging more than 1 U.S. cent on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The fall was triggered off by heavy selling of the Kiwi
following negative news about the impact of weak Asian economies
on Australia and New Zealand, both large traders with Asia.
</P>
<P>
A dealer said there were talks in the financial market of one
sell order by a North American institution of about 1 billion NZ
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Dealers' views about the Kiwi's prospects varied, with one
forecasting that the currency would fall to as low as 60 U.S.
cents in the next three to six months. But most of them seem to
believe that it would not go higher.
</P>
<P>
The investment company Goldman Sachs said recent difficulties
in Southeast Asia were likely to be an economic shock for
Australia and New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
The Asian currency devaluations would slash import demand from
the Asian region, which took 52 percent of Australian exports and
26 percent of New Zealand exports.
</P>
<P>
However, the NZ Manufacturers' Federation sees the decline in
the Kiwi as a two-edged sword for manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
On one hand, said federation chief executive Simon Arnold, weak
currencies, weak consumer demand and infrastructural problems in
Southeast Asian countries could reduce sales for NZ manufacturers
exporting to the region.
</P>
<P>
On the other, he said, a weaker NZ dollar would allow exporters
to boost their ability to compete in Asian markets.
</P>
<P>
It would benefit exporters by increasing their overall
competitiveness in international markets, he argued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971024.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-10-24 </DATE_TIME>
