<HEADLINE> Pak PM Leaves for Edinburgh Commonwealth Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 23 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif left here tonight for Edinburgh, Scotland, to attend
the four-day Commonwealth Summit scheduled for October 24-27.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said in a statement before his departure, "As we
endeavor to work the economic miracle in Pakistan, we seek greater
foreign investments, promotion of trade and broadening of
developmental horizons."
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth comprising developed and developing countries
provides a unique forum to address these issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in Edinburgh, Sharif is expected to meet with
his counterparts from Commonwealth states, including Indian Prime
Minister Inder K. Gujral, to discuss bilateral and regional
issues.
</P>
<P>
The Edinburgh meeting will focus on trade, investment and
development, issues of highest priority to Pakistan, according to
Sharif.
</P>
<P>
Sharif will make an address at the Edinburgh meeting, in which
he will apprise the heads of the Commonwealth member states of
Pakistan's stand on various regional and international issues.
</P>
