<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, October 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greece was almost brought to a standstill Thursday as
a 24-hour general strike nationwide was called by the General
Confederation of Greek Workers (GSEE), the largest labor union in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Striking workers throughout the country held rallies and
marched to the streets in demand for higher wages, a 35-hour
working week and no cuts in social security benefits.
</P>
<P>
Banks and many shops remained closed all day while transport
were disrupted for several hours due to stoppages. (Greece-Strikes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Major stock markets in Europe all extended
Wednesday's losses and ended sharply lower Thursday as shockwaves
from Hong Kong's plunge rocked the markets.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 index had dropped 222 points at one stage
early today before closing at 4,991.50 points, down 3.06 percent
or 157.3 points.
</P>
<P>
Shares prices in Frankfurt also slid, with the DAX-30 index
closing at 3,977.26, down 194.19 points or 4.66 percent, once
again below the key 4,000-point level, as the plunge in Hong Kong
hurt sentiment.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the CAC-40 index followed the whole world and ended
101.19 points lower at 2,856.87. (Europe-Stock-Slide)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
BC-Israel-Palestinians-Aqsa Mosque
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Palestinian religious and resistance organizations
warned Thursday against any Israeli attempt to "repair" or "demolish"
the holy Muslim shrine Aqsa Mosque in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic Council of Palestine said the destruction of any
parts of the Aqsa Mosque would violate the conventions protecting
civil rights under occupation and such results would be massive
destruction in the entire region, according to the Jerusalem Media
and Communication Center (JMCC).
</P>
<P>
Israel announced earlier this week that it was ready to
"repair" the Aqsa Mosque. (Israel-Palestinians-Aqsa Mosque)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PRAGUE -- Czech Foreign Minister Josef Zieleniec Thursday
unexpectedly rendered his resignation, saying that he found
difficulty in carrying our his duties.
</P>
<P>
President Vaclav Havel accepted Zieleniec's resignation after
consulting with Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus.
</P>
<P>
Zieleniec, 51, told a news conference that he was also quitting
as deputy chairman of the ruling Civic Democratic Party.
(Czech-FM-Resignation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
